{"title_page": "International Settlement (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1938 film by Eugene Forde}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = International Settlement\n| image          = International Settlement poster.jpg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Eugene Forde]]\n| producer       = [[Darryl F. Zanuck]]<br>[[Sol M. Wurtzel]]\n| writer         = [[Lou Breslow]]<br>[[Frank Fenton (writer)|Frank Fenton]]\n| narrator       =\n| music          = [[Samuel Kaylin]]\n| editing        = [[Nick DeMaggio]]\n| starring       = [[Dolores del R\u00edo]]<br>[[George Sanders]]<br>[[June Lang]]\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1938|02|04}}\n| runtime        = 75 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''International Settlement''''' is a 1938 American [[drama film]] directed by [[Eugene Forde]] and starring [[Dolores del R\u00edo]], [[George Sanders]] and [[June Lang]]. It is set in the [[Shanghai International Settlement]] during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War|Sino-Japanese War]]. In the film, a [[gun runner]] falls in love with a beautiful French singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/37700 |title=International Settlement (1938) &#124; BFI |website=Ftvdb.bfi.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n1938's \"International Settlement\" refers to the heart of [[Shanghai]] China (the shooting title was \"Shanghai Deadline\"), where Western foreign powers had long controlled a protected enclave divided among 13 nations.  The film opens as Japanese forces have successfully overrun Peiping (modern day Beijing) in the north and are now heading for Shanghai. Somewhat like Casablanca's famous opening, this conflict is introduced with a twirling globe leading us to China, interspersed with genuine  [[newsreel]] footage of Japanese bombers attacking Peiping and Chinese refugees fleeing south, while a solemn voice intones the threat of oncoming war.  \n  \nFuture Academy-award-winner [[George Sanders]] in his first leading man role in Hollywood, plays Del Forbes, a vagabond adventurer with a dapper mustache, sailing for China, and broke enough to agree to impersonate a fellow passenger, ailing munitions dealer Zabellu (Pedro de Cordoba). Too ill to leave the ship, Zabellu pays Forbes to impersonate him in an illegal arms deal for which he's owed some 200,000 pounds (\"That's a nearly a million dollars!!\" Forbes exclaims helpfully). Since no one in Shanghai knows who either man is, Forbes agrees.\n\nForbes gets the last hotel room In a British sector crowded with frightened guests escaping from the Japanese invasion of [[Peiping]] in the north. Playing the suave, slightly condescending British cad that would become his trademark, Sander's Forbes ignores the annoying advances of a naive American girl Joyce,( [[June Lang]]), and instead falls hard for Lenore ([[Dolores del R\u00edo]]), a stunning [[nightclub singer]] he first meets when she breaks into his room and tries to kill him.  As she not only misses but is far too beautiful to turn over to the police, Forbes promptly invites her to dinner.  But first he rickshaws to the \"native city\" - the Chinese quarter outside the Settlement - to carry through the deal with shady Joseph Lang ([[Harold Huber]]) and his partner Murdock ([[John Carradine]] in another early role).  He fights off an attack as he leaves with the money but when he delivers it to the ship, he learns Zabellu has died of natural causes.\n\nForbes is now walking around Shanghai with a million dollars in pounds around his waist\u2014and love in his heart.  A romantic dinner ensues; a night of passion promised. \"An unusual thing is happening to me,\" he tells Lenore in his dulcet British murmur. \"I'm beginning to care whether I'm alive.\"\n\nUnaware that she's the wife of a shady American munitions dealer, Monte Silver ([[Leon Ames]]) who also wants the money, Forbes believes Lenore when she brings him to the Green Dragon, a bar in the Chinese quarter, where Monte Silver is waiting for him. Just when Sander's character realizes he's been set up by the woman he loves, Japanese bombers start attacking Shanghai; the two men struggle and Monte shoots Forbes in the arm. Lenore rushes into the room, where wounded Forbes has just enough time to congratulate her on her deception when the bar is hit by a bomb. Silver staggers off, leaving Lenore and Forbes unconscious in its wreckage.\n\nAs backlot explosions are  intercut with actual 1937 newsreel footage of the [[bombing of Shanghai]] by the Japanese, Lenore wakens and braves the bombing in the streets to search for a doctor for the dying Forbes, and finds one bandaging wounded Chinese peasants.  Doctor Wong [[Keye Luke]] is a rare Hollywood role of an educated, compassionate and bi-lingual Asian professional- in fact, he plays the only intelligent, decent man in the entire film.  Dr. Wong frees the still-unconscious Forbes from the beam that's crushed him and explains  - as bombs explode over them -  that only a transfusion will save the man, risky to attempt outside a hospital. Lenore begs to donate her blood, so Dr. Wong tests her compatibility, then improvises a workable transfusion which saves Forbes's life.  When Forbes wakes, though, unaware of what she's just done, he bitterly rejects Lenore again before collapsing. Lenore rushes off to get help and finds June Lang and her buddy, an equally ditzy newsreel cameraman ([[Dick Baldwin]]) in the Chinese quarter but they arrive too late:  the building where Forbes lay has been destroyed.\n\nWith her husband executing everyone in his way, he and Lenore board a ship heading for America with the million dollars in pounds.  But - surprise!- Forbes is there too, alive if not entirely happy until Joyce explains to the bitter man all Lenore has done to save him. He visits her cabin just in time to watch Lenore point her gun at her soon-to-be-ex-husband, and take the money and leave with Forbes.  She doesn't actually kill the man, but conveniently someone else does, and everyone who deserves to lives happily ever after.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] - Lenore Dixon\n* [[George Sanders]] - Del Forbes\n* [[June Lang]] - Joyce Parker\n* [[Dick Baldwin]] - Wally Burton\n* [[Ruth Terry]] - Vera Dale\n* [[John Carradine]] - Murdock\n* [[Keye Luke]] - Doctor Wong\n* [[Harold Huber]] - Joseph Lang\n* [[Leon Ames (actor)|Leon Ames]] - Monte Silvers\n* [[Pedro de Cordoba]] - Maurice Zabello\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0030274}}\n\n{{Darryl F. Zanuck}}\n\n[[Category:1938 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:1930s drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Eugene Forde]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Darryl F. Zanuck]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Shanghai International Settlement]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1938 film by Eugene Forde}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = International Settlement\n| image          = International Settlement poster.jpg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Eugene Forde]]\n| producer       = [[Darryl F. Zanuck]]<br>[[Sol M. Wurtzel]]\n| writer         = [[Lou Breslow]]<br>[[Frank Fenton (writer)|Frank Fenton]]\n| narrator       =\n| music          = [[Samuel Kaylin]]\n| editing        = [[Nick DeMaggio]]\n| starring       = [[Dolores del R\u00edo]]<br>[[George Sanders]]<br>[[June Lang]]\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1938|02|04}}\n| runtime        = 75 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''International Settlement''''' is a 1938 American [[drama film]] directed by [[Eugene Forde]] and starring [[Dolores del R\u00edo]], [[George Sanders]] and [[June Lang]]. It is set in the [[Shanghai International Settlement]] during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War|Sino-Japanese War]]. In the film, a [[gun runner]] falls in love with a beautiful French singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/37700 |title=International Settlement (1938) &#124; BFI |website=Ftvdb.bfi.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n1938's \"International Settlement\" refers to the heart of [[Shanghai]] China (the shooting title was \"Shanghai Deadline\"), where Western foreign powers had long controlled a protected enclave divided among 13 nations.  The film opens as Japanese forces have successfully overrun Peiping (modern day Beijing) in the north and are now heading for Shanghai. Somewhat like Casablanca's famous opening, this conflict is introduced with a twirling globe leading us to China, interspersed with genuine  [[newsreel]] footage of Japanese bombers attacking Peiping and Chinese refugees fleeing south, while a solemn voice intones the threat of oncoming war.  \n  \nFuture Academy-award-winner [[George Sanders]] in his first leading man role in Hollywood, plays Del Forbes, a vagabond adventurer with a dapper mustache, sailing for China, and broke enough to agree to impersonate a fellow passenger, ailing munitions dealer Zabellu (Pedro de Cordoba). Too ill to leave the ship, Zabellu pays Forbes to impersonate him in an illegal arms deal for which he's owed some 200,000 pounds (\"That's a nearly a million dollars!!\" Forbes exclaims helpfully). Since no one in Shanghai knows who either man is, Forbes agrees.\n\nForbes gets the last hotel room In a British sector crowded with frightened guests escaping from the Japanese invasion of [[Peiping]] in the north. Playing the suave, slightly condescending British cad that would become his trademark, Sander's Forbes ignores the annoying advances of a naive American girl Joyce,( [[June Lang]]), and instead falls hard for Lenore ([[Dolores del R\u00edo]]), a stunning [[nightclub singer]] he first meets when she breaks into his room and tries to kill him.  As she not only misses but is far too beautiful to turn over to the police, Forbes promptly invites her to dinner.  But first he rickshaws to the \"native city\" - the Chinese quarter outside the Settlement - to carry through the deal with shady Joseph Lang ([[Harold Huber]]) and his partner Murdock ([[John Carradine]] in another early role).  He fights off an attack as he leaves with the money but when he delivers it to the ship, he learns Zabellu has died of natural causes.\n\nForbes is now walking around Shanghai with a million dollars in pounds around his waist\u2014and love in his heart.  A romantic dinner ensues; a night of passion promised. \"An unusual thing is happening to me,\" he tells Lenore in his dulcet British murmur. \"I'm beginning to care whether I'm alive.\"\n\nUnaware that she's the wife of a shady American munitions dealer, Monte Silver ([[Leon Ames]]) who also wants the money, Forbes believes Lenore when she brings him to the Green Dragon, a bar in the Chinese quarter, where Monte Silver is waiting for him. Just when Sander's character realizes he's been set up by the woman he loves, Japanese bombers start attacking Shanghai; the two men struggle and Monte shoots Forbes in the arm. Lenore rushes into the room, where wounded Forbes has just enough time to congratulate her on her deception when the bar is hit by a bomb. Silver staggers off, leaving Lenore and Forbes unconscious in its wreckage.\n\nAs backlot explosions are  intercut with actual 1937 newsreel footage of the [[bombing of Shanghai]] by the Japanese, Lenore wakens and braves the bombing in the streets to search for a doctor for the dying Forbes, and finds one bandaging wounded Chinese peasants.  Doctor Wong [[Keye Luke]] is a rare Hollywood role of an educated, compassionate and bi-lingual Asian professional- in fact, he plays the only intelligent, decent man in the entire film.  Dr. Wong frees the still-unconscious Forbes from the beam that's crushed him and explains  - as bombs explode over them -  that only a transfusion will save the man, risky to attempt outside a hospital. Lenore begs to donate her blood, so Dr. Wong tests her compatibility, then improvises a workable transfusion which saves Forbes's life.  When Forbes wakes, though, unaware of what she's just done, he bitterly rejects Lenore again before collapsing. Lenore rushes off to get help and finds June Lang and her buddy, an equally ditzy newsreel cameraman ([[Dick Baldwin]]) in the Chinese quarter but they arrive too late:  the building where Forbes lay has been destroyed.\n\nWith her husband executing everyone in his way, he and Lenore board a ship heading for America with the million dollars in pounds.  But - surprise!- Forbes is there too, alive if not entirely happy until Joyce explains to the bitter man all Lenore has done to save him. He visits her cabin just in time to watch Lenore point her gun at her soon-to-be-ex-husband, and take the money and leave with Forbes.  She doesn't actually kill the man, but conveniently someone else does, and everyone who deserves to lives happily ever after.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] - Lenore Dixon\n* [[George Sanders]] - Del Forbes\n* [[June Lang]] - Joyce Parker\n* [[Dick Baldwin]] - Wally Burton\n* [[Ruth Terry]] - Vera Dale\n* [[John Carradine]] - Murdock\n* [[Keye Luke]] - Doctor Wong\n* [[Harold Huber]] - Joseph Lang\n* [[Leon Ames (actor)|Leon Ames]] - Monte Silvers\n* [[Pedro de Cordoba]] - Maurice Zabello\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0030274}}\n\n{{Darryl F. Zanuck}}\n\n[[Category:1938 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:1930s drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Eugene Forde]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Darryl F. Zanuck]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Shanghai International Settlement]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast:Template:Cast listing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Settlement_(film)"}
{"title_page": "DoorDash", "text_new": "{{short description|On-demand restaurant food delivery service}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:DoorDash}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = DoorDash Inc.\n| logo = DoorDash Logo.svg\n| type = Privately held company\n| industry = Logistics\n| founded = {{start date and age|2013|6}}<br>Palo Alto, California, U.S.\n| founders = Andy Fang<br>Stanley Tang<br>Evan Moore<br>Tony Xu\n| hq_location_city = Rialto Building<br>San Francisco, [[California]], U.S.\n| key_people = Andy Fang ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]]) <br> Tony Xu ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br> Prabir Adarkar ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])<br> Christopher Payne ([[Chief operating officer|COO]])\n| num_employees = 7,549 (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://craft.co/doordash|title=Revolut Company Profile|publisher=Craft|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n| revenue = $900 million (Dec 2019)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://craft.co/doordash/metrics|title=DoorDash stock price, funding rounds, valuation and financials|publisher=Craft|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| website = {{url|https://doordash.com/en-US/}}\n}}\n\n'''DoorDash Inc.''' is a [[San Francisco]]-based on-demand prepared [[food delivery]] service<ref>{{Cite web |title = DoorDash About Page|url = https://www.doordash.com/about//|website = DoorDash|accessdate = June 20, 2015}}</ref> founded in 2013 by [[Stanford University|Stanford]] students Andy Fang, Stanley Tang, Tony Xu and Evan Moore.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/11/doordash-wants-to-own-the-last-mile/|title=DOORDASH WANTS TO OWN THE LAST MILE|author=Steven Levy|date=November 9, 2015|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |access-date=May 25, 2019}}</ref> A [[Y Combinator (company)|Y Combinator]]\u2013backed company, DoorDash is one of several [[technology companies]] that uses [[logistics]] services to offer food delivery from restaurants on-demand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/sanfrancisco/filler-app-how-tech-companies-are-disrupting-restaurant-delivery/Content?oid=2948629|title=Filler App: How Tech Companies Are Disrupting Restaurant Delivery|author=Anna Roth|date=June 26, 2013|publisher=[[SF Weekly]]|accessdate=February 26, 2014}}</ref> DoorDash launched in [[Palo Alto, California|Palo Alto]] and, as of May 2019, had expanded to more than 4,000 cities and offered a 340,000 selection of stores across the US and Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.doordash.com/fueling-the-last-mile-3ae0a6b45ea0|title=Fueling the Last Mile|last=DoorDash|date=2019-05-24|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> The company is currently worth more than $13 billion and is the largest [[Third party|third-party]] delivery service in the world, surpassing [[Grubhub]] in 2019.<ref> https://www.restaurantdive.com/news/doordash-overtakes-grubhub-in-delivery-market-share/550338/ </ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/11/16/why-chuys-is-fighting-to-control-food-delivery-dat.aspx|title=Why Chuy's Is Fighting to Control Food Delivery Data|last=Quast|first=Jon|date=2019-11-16|website=The Motley Fool|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDoorDash has raised more than $700 million<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4497a7e-1d12-11e8-956a-43db76e69936/|title=SoftBank leads $535m investment in food delivery start-up|author=Richard Waters|date=March 1, 2018|publisher=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> over several financing rounds from investors including [[Charles River Ventures]], SV Angel, [[Khosla Ventures]], [[Sequoia Capital]], [[SoftBank Group|SoftBank]], GIC,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2018/03/01/data-sheet-doordash-expand-delivery/|title=Data Sheet\u2014What DoorDash Plans to Do With Another Half a Billion Dollars of Capital|website=fortune.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref> and [[Kleiner Perkins]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = DoorDash Crunchbase|url = https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/doordash|website = Crunchbase|accessdate = June 20, 2015}}</ref> As of May 2019, DoorDash's [[post-money valuation]] is $12.6 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bizcarson/2019/05/23/doordash-12-billion-valuation-series-g-funding/|title=DoorDash Is Now Worth $12.6 Billion After New $600 Million Investment|last=Carson|first=Biz|date=May 23, 2019|website=forbes.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Oct 10, 2019}}</ref> In October 2017, CFO Mike Dinsdale left DoorDash less than a year after he started working for the company.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dickey |first=Megan Rose |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/25/doordash-cfo-leaves-less-than-one-year-after-joining/ |title=DoorDash CFO leaves less than one year after joining |work=[[TechCrunch]] |date=2017-10-25 |accessdate=2017-10-26 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, DoorDash raised $535 million in a Series D round led by the [[SoftBank Group]] with participation from existing investors [[Sequoia Capital]], [[GIC Private Limited|GIC]] and [[Wellcome Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bizcarson/2018/03/01/doordash-raises-535-million-to-fuel-food-delivery-war/|title=DoorDash Raises $535 Million To Fuel Food Delivery War|first=Biz|last=Carson|website=Forbes}}</ref> In April 2018, DoorDash ventured into grocery delivery through a partnership with [[Walmart]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/24/17275016/walmart-grocery-deliveries-doordash|title=Walmart tests grocery deliveries via DoorDash|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=24 April 2018|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in December 2018 that DoorDash overtook [[Uber Eats]] to hold the second position in total US food delivery sales, behind only [[GrubHub]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1549084/doordash-overtook-uber-eats-in-us-online-food-delivery-second-measure-finds/|title=DoorDash has overtaken Uber Eats in US online food delivery|first=Alison|last=Griswold|website=Quartz|accessdate=Jul 16, 2019}}</ref> By March 2019, it had exceeded GrubHub in total sales, at 27.6% of the on-demand delivery market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/03/11/doordash-tops-grubhub-on-demand-food/|title=DoorDash Has Pulled Ahead of GrubHub, Uber Eats in the On-Demand Food Delivery Race|website=Fortune|accessdate=Jul 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019 DoorDash raised $400 million, bringing the company's total funding to $1.4 billon and reached a total valuation of $7.1 billion.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-17/doordash-is-said-to-be-raising-at-least-500-million-in-funding|title=DoorDash Is Raising at Least $500 Million in Funding|date=2019-05-22|access-date=2019-05-23|language=en}}</ref> As of May 2019 DoorDash is said to be raising an additional $600 million in funding.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> As of June 2019 DoorDash remains the leading [[food delivery]] service in the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1649997/doordash-unseats-grubhub-as-the-leader-in-us-online-food-delivery/|title=DoorDash has unseated Grubhub as the leader in US online food delivery|last=Griswold|first=Alison|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2019, DoorDash announced the acquisition of Caviar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2019/8/1/20750912/doordash-buys-caviar-food-delivery-app-410-million|title=The Great Flattening: What a Giant Delivery Merger Means for Your Dinner|last=Zhang|first=Jenny G.|date=2019-08-01|website=Eater|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>, a service specializing in food delivery from upscale urban-area restaurants that typically do not offer delivery, from [[Square, Inc.]] The purchase price was $410 million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Griffith |first1=Erin |title=DoorDash Buys Rival, Caviar, for $410 Million |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/01/technology/doordash-cavier-deal.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=2 August 2019 |publisher=The New York Times Company |pages=B8}}</ref> The company announced later in August 2019 that it had acquired Scotty Labs, a tele-operations startup company that focuses on self-driving and remote-controlled vehicle technology. The financial details of the acquisition were not publicly disclosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/08/20/doordash-acquires-autonomous-driving-startup-scotty-labs/|title=DoorDash acquires autonomous driving startup Scotty Labs|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/21/20826327/doordash-acquires-scotty-labs-autonomous-vehicle-remote-control-startup|title=DoorDash takes another step toward automated food delivery|last=Porter|first=Jon|date=2019-08-21|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2019, DoorDash announced it will be partnering with Mercato, an e-commerce platform, to help expand its business and reach independent grocers and specialty stores.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.grocerydive.com/news/doordash-makes-another-move-toward-grocery-with-mercato/561901/ |title=DoorDash makes another move toward grocery with  |website=Grocery Dive |language=en-US |access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> This partnership allowed the company to make same-day deliveries, servicing 750 independent grocers across 22 states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-next-big-gig-for-delivery-companies-is-your-groceries-11570013400|title=Postmates, DoorDash Want to Deliver Your Groceries, Too|last=Kang|first=Heather Haddon and Jaewon|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\nOn February 27, 2020, DoorDash announced that it has filed confidentially to go public.<ref>https://techcrunch.com/2020/02/27/doordash-ipo/</ref>\n\n==Criticism and lawsuits==\nOn November 6, 2015, [[In-N-Out Burger]] filed a lawsuit against DoorDash claiming trademark infringement and unfair competition.<ref>{{cite web|title=Complaint|url=http://www.pacermonitor.com/view/UKHLPEA/IN-N-OUT_BURGERS_v_DOORDASH__cacdce-15-01826__0001.0.pdf|website=PacerMonitor|accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref> Two months later the lawsuit was dismissed. DoorDash no longer delivers food from In-N-Out Burger.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-biz-doordash-restaurant-food-delivery-lawsuit-20180109-story.html|title=Suburban restaurant in DoorDash lawsuit: Stop delivering our food|first=Robert|last=Channick|website=chicagotribune.com}}</ref>\n\nBurger Antics has filed a lawsuit to get them to stop delivering their food after receiving complaints from their customers.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nDoorDash delivery workers filed a [[Class action|class action lawsuit]] for being misclassified as independent contractors. DoorDash agreed to pay $5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.htccms.com/2017/04/11/doordash-will-pay-5-million-settle-class-action-lawsuit-independent-contractors/|title=DoorDash will pay $5 million to settle class-action lawsuit over independent contractors|date=11 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2019 DoorDash confirmed 4.9 million customers, delivery workers and merchants had sensitive information stolen via a [[data breach]]. Those who joined the platform after April 5, 2018 were unaffected by the breach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/09/26/doordash-data-breach/|title=DoorDash confirms data breach affected 4.9 million customers, workers and merchants|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>  \n\n=== Tipped wage controversy ===\nIn July 2019, DoorDash attracted criticism from several publications, including ''[[The New York Times]]'', and later ''[[The Verge]]'' and ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', for its tipping policy, which, according to ''[[Gothamist]]'' \"really looks, feels, and smells like a swindle.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/21/nyregion/doordash-ubereats-food-app-delivery-bike.html|title=My Frantic Life as a Cab-Dodging, Tip-Chasing Food App Deliveryman|last=Newman|first=Andy|date=2019-07-21|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-07-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/7/22/20703434/delivery-app-tip-pay-theft-doordash-amazon-flex-instacart|title=Delivery apps like DoorDash are using your tips to pay workers\u2019 wages|last=Vincent|first=James|date=2019-07-22|website=[[The Verge]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2019/8/20/20825937/doordash-tipping-policy-still-not-changed-food-delivery-app-gig-economy|title=DoorDash is still pocketing workers\u2019 tips, almost a month after it promised to stop|last=Ghaffary|first=Shirin|date=2019-08-20|website=Vox|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref name=\"gothamist20190730\">{{cite web|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=July 30, 2019|last=Lampen|first=Claire|title=Brooklyn Man Sues DoorDash Over Grifty, Misleading Tip Policy|url=https://gothamist.com/2019/07/30/doordash_tipping_lawsuit.php|access-date=August 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805221244/https://gothamist.com/2019/07/30/doordash_tipping_lawsuit.php|archive-date=August 5, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> Drivers receive a guaranteed minimum per order, which is paid by DoorDash by default. When a customer adds a tip, instead of going to the driver, it first goes to the company up to the point that the company no longer has to pay the driver the guaranteed minimum. Drivers then only receive the part of the tip that exceeds the minimum. DoorDash announced plans to change its pay model shortly after the ''New York Times'' story.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/24/nyregion/doordash-tip-policy.html</ref> A week after the ''Times'' article, a DoorDash customer filed a [[class action lawsuit]] against the company for its \"materially false and misleading\" tipping policy.<ref name=\"gothamist20190730\" /><ref name=\"post20190729\">{{cite web|work=[[New York Post]]|date=July 29, 1029|last=Wayt|first=Theo|title=Brooklyn man sues DoorDash for 'misleading' tipping policy|url=https://nypost.com/2019/07/29/brooklyn-man-sues-doordash-for-misleading-tipping-policy/}}</ref> On August 20, 2019, [[Vox (website)|''Vox'']] released an article titled \"DoorDash is still pocketing workers' tips, almost a month after it promised to stop\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2019/8/20/20825937/doordash-tipping-policy-still-not-changed-food-delivery-app-gig-economy|title=DoorDash is still pocketing workers\u2019 tips, almost a month after it promised to stop|last=Ghaffary|first=Shirin|date=2019-08-20|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> On August 22, 2019, DoorDash announced an update to the tipping policy and promised to \"roll it out to all Dashers next month\" (that is, sometime in September 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/22/20828742/doordash-tipping-policy-change-drivers-earning-more-money|title=DoorDash breaks silence on driver tips, says it\u2019ll start paying them next month|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2019-08-22|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Grubhub]]\n*[[Deliveroo]]\n*[[Delivery Hero]]\n*[[Delivery.com]]\n*[[Postmates]]\n*[[Square, Inc.]]\n*[[Uber Eats]]\n*[[Swiggy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.doordash.com/en-US/}}\n\n{{Online food ordering}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Financial technology companies]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2013]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Y Combinator companies]]\n[[Category:Online food retailers of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|On-demand restaurant food delivery service}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:DoorDash}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = DoorDash Inc.\n| logo = DoorDash Logo.svg\n| type = Privately held company\n| industry = Logistics\n| founded = {{start date and age|2013|6}}<br>Palo Alto, California, U.S.\n| founders = Andy Fang<br>Stanley Tang<br>Evan Moore<br>Tony Xu\n| hq_location_city = Rialto Building<br>San Francisco, [[California]], U.S.\n| key_people = Andy Fang ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]]) <br> Tony Xu ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br> Prabir Adarkar ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])<br> Christopher Payne ([[Chief operating officer|COO]])\n| num_employees = 7,549 (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://craft.co/doordash|title=Revolut Company Profile|publisher=Craft|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n| revenue = $900 million (Dec 2019)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://craft.co/doordash/metrics|title=DoorDash stock price, funding rounds, valuation and financials|publisher=Craft|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| website = {{url|https://doordash.com/en-US/}}\n}}\n\n'''DoorDash Inc.''' is a San Francisco-based on-demand prepared [[food delivery]] service<ref>{{Cite web |title = DoorDash About Page|url = https://www.doordash.com/about//|website = DoorDash|accessdate = June 20, 2015}}</ref> founded in 2013 by [[Stanford University|Stanford]] students Andy Fang, Stanley Tang, Tony Xu and Evan Moore.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/11/doordash-wants-to-own-the-last-mile/|title=DOORDASH WANTS TO OWN THE LAST MILE|author=Steven Levy|date=November 9, 2015|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |access-date=May 25, 2019}}</ref> A [[Y Combinator (company)|Y Combinator]]\u2013backed company, DoorDash is one of several [[technology companies]] that uses [[logistics]] services to offer food delivery from restaurants on-demand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/sanfrancisco/filler-app-how-tech-companies-are-disrupting-restaurant-delivery/Content?oid=2948629|title=Filler App: How Tech Companies Are Disrupting Restaurant Delivery|author=Anna Roth|date=June 26, 2013|publisher=[[SF Weekly]]|accessdate=February 26, 2014}}</ref> DoorDash launched in [[Palo Alto, California|Palo Alto]] and, as of May 2019, had expanded to more than 4,000 cities and offered a 340,000 selection of stores across the US and Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.doordash.com/fueling-the-last-mile-3ae0a6b45ea0|title=Fueling the Last Mile|last=DoorDash|date=2019-05-24|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> The company is currently worth more than $13 billion and is the largest third-party delivery service in the world, surpassing [[Grubhub]] in 2019.<ref> https://www.restaurantdive.com/news/doordash-overtakes-grubhub-in-delivery-market-share/550338/ </ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/11/16/why-chuys-is-fighting-to-control-food-delivery-dat.aspx|title=Why Chuy's Is Fighting to Control Food Delivery Data|last=Quast|first=Jon|date=2019-11-16|website=The Motley Fool|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDoorDash has raised more than $700 million<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4497a7e-1d12-11e8-956a-43db76e69936/|title=SoftBank leads $535m investment in food delivery start-up|author=Richard Waters|date=March 1, 2018|publisher=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> over several financing rounds from investors including [[Charles River Ventures]], SV Angel, [[Khosla Ventures]], [[Sequoia Capital]], [[SoftBank Group|SoftBank]], GIC,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2018/03/01/data-sheet-doordash-expand-delivery/|title=Data Sheet\u2014What DoorDash Plans to Do With Another Half a Billion Dollars of Capital|website=fortune.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref> and [[Kleiner Perkins]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = DoorDash Crunchbase|url = https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/doordash|website = Crunchbase|accessdate = June 20, 2015}}</ref> As of May 2019, DoorDash's [[post-money valuation]] is $12.6 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bizcarson/2019/05/23/doordash-12-billion-valuation-series-g-funding/|title=DoorDash Is Now Worth $12.6 Billion After New $600 Million Investment|last=Carson|first=Biz|date=May 23, 2019|website=forbes.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Oct 10, 2019}}</ref> In October 2017, CFO Mike Dinsdale left DoorDash less than a year after he started working for the company.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dickey |first=Megan Rose |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/25/doordash-cfo-leaves-less-than-one-year-after-joining/ |title=DoorDash CFO leaves less than one year after joining |work=[[TechCrunch]] |date=2017-10-25 |accessdate=2017-10-26 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, DoorDash raised $535 million in a Series D round led by the [[SoftBank Group]] with participation from existing investors [[Sequoia Capital]], [[GIC Private Limited|GIC]] and [[Wellcome Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bizcarson/2018/03/01/doordash-raises-535-million-to-fuel-food-delivery-war/|title=DoorDash Raises $535 Million To Fuel Food Delivery War|first=Biz|last=Carson|website=Forbes}}</ref> In April 2018, DoorDash ventured into grocery delivery through a partnership with [[Walmart]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/24/17275016/walmart-grocery-deliveries-doordash|title=Walmart tests grocery deliveries via DoorDash|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=24 April 2018|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in December 2018 that DoorDash overtook [[Uber Eats]] to hold the second position in total US food delivery sales, behind only [[GrubHub]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1549084/doordash-overtook-uber-eats-in-us-online-food-delivery-second-measure-finds/|title=DoorDash has overtaken Uber Eats in US online food delivery|first=Alison|last=Griswold|website=Quartz|accessdate=Jul 16, 2019}}</ref> By March 2019, it had exceeded GrubHub in total sales, at 27.6% of the on-demand delivery market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/03/11/doordash-tops-grubhub-on-demand-food/|title=DoorDash Has Pulled Ahead of GrubHub, Uber Eats in the On-Demand Food Delivery Race|website=Fortune|accessdate=Jul 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019 DoorDash raised $400 million, bringing the company's total funding to $1.4 billon and reached a total valuation of $7.1 billion.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-17/doordash-is-said-to-be-raising-at-least-500-million-in-funding|title=DoorDash Is Raising at Least $500 Million in Funding|date=2019-05-22|access-date=2019-05-23|language=en}}</ref> As of May 2019 DoorDash is said to be raising an additional $600 million in funding.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> As of June 2019 DoorDash remains the leading [[food delivery]] service in the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1649997/doordash-unseats-grubhub-as-the-leader-in-us-online-food-delivery/|title=DoorDash has unseated Grubhub as the leader in US online food delivery|last=Griswold|first=Alison|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2019, DoorDash announced the acquisition of Caviar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2019/8/1/20750912/doordash-buys-caviar-food-delivery-app-410-million|title=The Great Flattening: What a Giant Delivery Merger Means for Your Dinner|last=Zhang|first=Jenny G.|date=2019-08-01|website=Eater|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>, a service specializing in food delivery from upscale urban-area restaurants that typically do not offer delivery, from [[Square, Inc.]] The purchase price was $410 million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Griffith |first1=Erin |title=DoorDash Buys Rival, Caviar, for $410 Million |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/01/technology/doordash-cavier-deal.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=2 August 2019 |publisher=The New York Times Company |pages=B8}}</ref> The company announced later in August 2019 that it had acquired Scotty Labs, a tele-operations startup company that focuses on self-driving and remote-controlled vehicle technology. The financial details of the acquisition were not publicly disclosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/08/20/doordash-acquires-autonomous-driving-startup-scotty-labs/|title=DoorDash acquires autonomous driving startup Scotty Labs|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/21/20826327/doordash-acquires-scotty-labs-autonomous-vehicle-remote-control-startup|title=DoorDash takes another step toward automated food delivery|last=Porter|first=Jon|date=2019-08-21|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2019, DoorDash announced it will be partnering with Mercato, an e-commerce platform, to help expand its business and reach independent grocers and specialty stores.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.grocerydive.com/news/doordash-makes-another-move-toward-grocery-with-mercato/561901/ |title=DoorDash makes another move toward grocery with  |website=Grocery Dive |language=en-US |access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> This partnership allowed the company to make same-day deliveries, servicing 750 independent grocers across 22 states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-next-big-gig-for-delivery-companies-is-your-groceries-11570013400|title=Postmates, DoorDash Want to Deliver Your Groceries, Too|last=Kang|first=Heather Haddon and Jaewon|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\nOn February 27, 2020, DoorDash announced that it has filed confidentially to go public.<ref>https://techcrunch.com/2020/02/27/doordash-ipo/</ref>\n\n==Criticism and lawsuits==\nOn November 6, 2015, [[In-N-Out Burger]] filed a lawsuit against DoorDash claiming trademark infringement and unfair competition.<ref>{{cite web|title=Complaint|url=http://www.pacermonitor.com/view/UKHLPEA/IN-N-OUT_BURGERS_v_DOORDASH__cacdce-15-01826__0001.0.pdf|website=PacerMonitor|accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref> Two months later the lawsuit was dismissed. DoorDash no longer delivers food from In-N-Out Burger.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-biz-doordash-restaurant-food-delivery-lawsuit-20180109-story.html|title=Suburban restaurant in DoorDash lawsuit: Stop delivering our food|first=Robert|last=Channick|website=chicagotribune.com}}</ref>\n\nBurger Antics has filed a lawsuit to get them to stop delivering their food after receiving complaints from their customers.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nDoorDash delivery workers filed a [[Class action|class action lawsuit]] for being misclassified as independent contractors. DoorDash agreed to pay $5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.htccms.com/2017/04/11/doordash-will-pay-5-million-settle-class-action-lawsuit-independent-contractors/|title=DoorDash will pay $5 million to settle class-action lawsuit over independent contractors|date=11 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2019 DoorDash confirmed 4.9 million customers, delivery workers and merchants had sensitive information stolen via a [[data breach]]. Those who joined the platform after April 5, 2018 were unaffected by the breach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/09/26/doordash-data-breach/|title=DoorDash confirms data breach affected 4.9 million customers, workers and merchants|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>  \n\n=== Tipped wage controversy ===\nIn July 2019, DoorDash attracted criticism from several publications, including ''[[The New York Times]]'', and later ''[[The Verge]]'' and ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', for its tipping policy, which, according to ''[[Gothamist]]'' \"really looks, feels, and smells like a swindle.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/21/nyregion/doordash-ubereats-food-app-delivery-bike.html|title=My Frantic Life as a Cab-Dodging, Tip-Chasing Food App Deliveryman|last=Newman|first=Andy|date=2019-07-21|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-07-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/7/22/20703434/delivery-app-tip-pay-theft-doordash-amazon-flex-instacart|title=Delivery apps like DoorDash are using your tips to pay workers\u2019 wages|last=Vincent|first=James|date=2019-07-22|website=[[The Verge]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2019/8/20/20825937/doordash-tipping-policy-still-not-changed-food-delivery-app-gig-economy|title=DoorDash is still pocketing workers\u2019 tips, almost a month after it promised to stop|last=Ghaffary|first=Shirin|date=2019-08-20|website=Vox|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref name=\"gothamist20190730\">{{cite web|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=July 30, 2019|last=Lampen|first=Claire|title=Brooklyn Man Sues DoorDash Over Grifty, Misleading Tip Policy|url=https://gothamist.com/2019/07/30/doordash_tipping_lawsuit.php|access-date=August 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805221244/https://gothamist.com/2019/07/30/doordash_tipping_lawsuit.php|archive-date=August 5, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> Drivers receive a guaranteed minimum per order, which is paid by DoorDash by default. When a customer adds a tip, instead of going to the driver, it first goes to the company up to the point that the company no longer has to pay the driver the guaranteed minimum. Drivers then only receive the part of the tip that exceeds the minimum. DoorDash announced plans to change its pay model shortly after the ''New York Times'' story.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/24/nyregion/doordash-tip-policy.html</ref> A week after the ''Times'' article, a DoorDash customer filed a [[class action lawsuit]] against the company for its \"materially false and misleading\" tipping policy.<ref name=\"gothamist20190730\" /><ref name=\"post20190729\">{{cite web|work=[[New York Post]]|date=July 29, 1029|last=Wayt|first=Theo|title=Brooklyn man sues DoorDash for 'misleading' tipping policy|url=https://nypost.com/2019/07/29/brooklyn-man-sues-doordash-for-misleading-tipping-policy/}}</ref> On August 20, 2019, [[Vox (website)|''Vox'']] released an article titled \"DoorDash is still pocketing workers' tips, almost a month after it promised to stop\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2019/8/20/20825937/doordash-tipping-policy-still-not-changed-food-delivery-app-gig-economy|title=DoorDash is still pocketing workers\u2019 tips, almost a month after it promised to stop|last=Ghaffary|first=Shirin|date=2019-08-20|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> On August 22, 2019, DoorDash announced an update to the tipping policy and promised to \"roll it out to all Dashers next month\" (that is, sometime in September 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/22/20828742/doordash-tipping-policy-change-drivers-earning-more-money|title=DoorDash breaks silence on driver tips, says it\u2019ll start paying them next month|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2019-08-22|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Grubhub]]\n*[[Deliveroo]]\n*[[Delivery Hero]]\n*[[Delivery.com]]\n*[[Postmates]]\n*[[Square, Inc.]]\n*[[Uber Eats]]\n*[[Swiggy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.doordash.com/en-US/}}\n\n{{Online food ordering}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Financial technology companies]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2013]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Y Combinator companies]]\n[[Category:Online food retailers of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Adam Naa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DoorDash"}
{"title_page": "Stay-at-home order", "text_new": "{{Globalize|1=article|2=United States|date=March 2020}}\n{{Redirect-distinguish|Shelter-in-place order|Shelter in place}}\n{{Short description|Quarantine strategy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020|cs1-dates=y}}\nA '''stay-at-home order''' (North America) or a '''movement control order''' (Southeast Asia) is an order from an authority to restrict movements of population as a mass [[quarantine]] strategy for suppressing or mitigating an [[epidemic]] or [[pandemic]] by ordering residents to stay home except for essential tasks or going to work in essential businesses. In many cases, outdoor activities are allowed. Nonessential businesses are either closed or changed to be [[working from home]].<ref name=\"nbcchicago\">{{cite news |title=What You Can and Cannot Do During a Stay-at-Home or Shelter-in-Place Order |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/what-you-can-and-cannot-do-during-a-stay-at-home-or-shelter-in-place-order/2241024/ |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=NBC Chicago |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> In some regions, it has been implemented as a round-the-clock [[curfew]]<ref>{{cite news |title=City of Birmingham under Shelter in Place in order |publisher=[[WBRC]]|date=March 24, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |url=https://www.wsfa.com/2020/03/24/birminghams-mayor-proposes-ordinance-shelter-place-during-coronavirus-outbreak/}}</ref> or called a '''shelter-in-place order''',<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus stay-at-home and shelter-in-place orders, by state|work=[[USA Today]]|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/03/30/coronavirus-stay-home-shelter-in-place-orders-by-state/5092413002/}}</ref> but it is not to be confused with a [[shelter in place]] situation.<ref>{{cite news|title=In pandemic, word definitions shift and new lexicon emerges|first=Matt|last=Sedensky|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=AP News|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020|url=https://apnews.com/d7b3035038a786d4aaed35e9b672a9d2}}</ref> Similar measures have been used around the world, but the term '''lockdown''' is used instead.<ref name=\"Kottasov\u00e1\">{{cite news |last=Kottasov\u00e1 |first=Ivana |title=Coronavirus lockdowns: 24 hours of confusion around the world |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/health/restrictions-lockdowns-confusion-coronavirus-intl/index.html |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Some officials have a concern that the word lockdown may send a wrong message for people to incorrectly think that it includes door-to-door searching for infected people to be forced into quarantines similar to the [[Wuhan lockdown]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Sedensky |first=Matt |title=In pandemic, word definitions shift and new lexicon emerges |url=https://apnews.com/d7b3035038a786d4aaed35e9b672a9d2 |access-date=24 March 2020 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n{{See also|Shelter in place|Lockdown}}\nThe term ''[[lockdown]]'' was used by the media and the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) to describe the action taken in January 2020 by the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|government of China]] to restrict movements of people in order to control the outbreak of [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|Wuhan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wuhan lockdown 'unprecedented', shows commitment to contain virus: WHO representative in China |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-who-idUSKBN1ZM1G9 |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> When Italian authorities imposed [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|a strict quarantine order]] in the northern part of the country, the media also used the term lockdown, which was used for [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|Spain]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]], as well as other countries around the world.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Venice Carnival closes as Italy imposes lockdown |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51602007 |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=[[BBC]] |date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Sam |title=Spain orders nationwide lockdown to battle coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/14/spain-government-set-to-order-nationwide-coronavirus-lockdown |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mcardle |first=Mairead |title=France Announces Two-Week Lockdown, Orders Residents to Stay Home |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/news/coronavirus-pandemic-france-announces-two-week-lockdown-orders-residents-to-stay-home/ |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=[[National Review]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Secon |first1=Holly |last2=Frias |first2=Lauren |last3=McFall-Johnsen |first3=Morgan |title=A running list of countries that are on lockdown because of the coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/countries-on-lockdown-coronavirus-italy-2020-3 |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Although it is not a technical term in [[public health]] or laws, the media continued to use ''lockdown'' to describe the actions taken by these governments.<ref>{{cite news |last=Resnick |first=Brian |title=Italy and China used lockdowns to slow the coronavirus. Could we? |url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2020/3/10/21171464/coronavirus-us-lockdown-travel-restriction-italy |access-date=25 March 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media, LLC.]] |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> As the lockdowns were expanded to other countries, there was a shift in the definitions. Measures are less restrictive and other terms emerged in attempts to differentiate from the most restrictive measure in China.<ref name=Kottasov\u00e1/>\n\n[[File:Loyalsock Volunteer Fire Co COVID-19 warning sign.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Many jurisdictions in the United States have referred to their stay-at-home orders by the slogan \"Stay home, stay safe.\"]]\n\nWhen the authorities in [[San Francisco Bay Area]] issued an order in March 2020 for residents to stay home to control the outbreak of COVID-19, they called it a ''shelter-in-place order''.<ref name=sfchronicle>{{cite news |last=Ravani |first=Sarah |title=Bay Area coronavirus decision: Behind the scenes of nation\u2019s first shelter-in-place order |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Bay-Area-coronavirus-decision-Behind-the-scenes-15148425.php |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> People were not familiar with it as the term ''[[shelter in place]]'' had been used in other emergency situations such as an [[active shooter]] which would require seeking a safe place to hide within the same building that the person already occupies until the situation is resolved.<ref>{{cite news |last=Waldrop |first=Theresa |title=Self-isolation, quarantine and California's stay-at-home order: What the terms mean and how they differ |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/19/health/shelter-in-place-isolation-quarantine-definition/index.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> This caused confusion to the residents under the order on what exactly they are supposed to do.<ref>{{cite news |last=Singal |first=Jesse |title=Stop Using the Term \u2018Shelter in Place\u2019 for the Coronavirus Crisis |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/shelter-in-place-in-coronavirus-crisis-what-does-it-mean.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Intelligencer (website)|Intelligencer]] |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Gavin Newsom|Governor Gavin Newsom]] announced the state-wide order for California which would supersede the Bay Area's order, he used the term ''stay-at-home order'' instead.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tolan |first=Casey |title=Coronavirus: Newsom\u2019s stay-at-home order differs from the Bay Area\u2019s shelter-in-place rules. Now what happens? |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2020/03/20/coronavirus-california-stay-home-order-local-bay-area-covid-19-rules/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[The Mercury News]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Other US states started using the new term when they announced their statewide order.<ref name=npr>{{cite news |title=New York, Illinois Governors Issue Stay At Home Orders, Following California's Lead |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/20/818952589/coronavirus-n-y-gov-cuomo-says-100-of-workforce-must-stay-home |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> In a press conference, [[Andrew Cuomo|Governor Andrew Cuomo]] of New York criticized anyone using the term shelter in place for his stay-at-home order as it would invoke panic due to its association with active shooting situations or [[nuclear war]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Corey |first=Rebecca |title=Shelter in place, stay at home, quarantine: What do coronavirus restrictions mean? |url=https://news.yahoo.com/shelter-in-place-stay-at-home-quarantine-what-do-coronavirus-restrictions-mean-145017819.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Yahoo News]] |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Lockdowns in the United States===\nIn the United States, the term ''lockdown'' has been widely used in emergency preparedness. A lockdown procedure requires immediate actions in hiding and locking all doors. Additional actions may be taken such as turning off lights and staying away from windows.<ref>{{cite web |title=Emergency Lockdown Planning Considerations |url=https://emilms.fema.gov/IS360/groups/217.html |publisher=[[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Guide for Developing High-Quality School Emergency Operations Plans |date=2013 |publisher=[[U.S. Department of Education]] |url=https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/20130726-1922-25045-3850/rems_k_12_guide.pdf |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Students in all grade levels around the country participate in lockdown drills on a regular basis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pinsker |first=Joe |title=When Was the Last Time American Children Were So Afraid? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2019/05/lockdown-drill-fear/589090/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=The Atlantic |date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe word ''lockdown'' can also be associated a [[martial law]] to mean that people cannot leave their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hays |first=Holly V. |title=Shelter in place, stay at home, lockdown: What the terms mean |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/health/2020/03/23/shelter-place-stay-home-lockdown-what-terms-mean/2900320001/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Indy Star]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> In an attempt to avoid confusion, [[Lori Lightfoot|Mayor Lori Lightfoot]] of Chicago made a comment about the stay-at-home order of Illinois by trying to differentiate it from a lockdown or a martial law.<ref name=\"tribune\">{{cite news |last=Munks |first=Jamie |title=Gov. Pritzker issued a stay-at-home order. What does that mean? |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/coronavirus/ct-coronavirus-what-is-shelter-in-place-20200320-rvyzf7h24ff5tfnvve5kz6g6b4-story.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen states and counties across the United States issued an order to have residents to remain home, they either called it shelter-in-place order or stay-at-home order. It has been clarified that these orders are not lockdowns because residents are allowed to go in and out of their homes in limited circumstances.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hauck |first=Grace |title=These states are ordering residents to stay home or shelter in place. What does that mean? |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/nation/2020/03/21/coronavirus-lockdown-orders-shelter-place-stay-home-state-list/2891193001/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Courier Journal]] |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Some jurisdictions have determined that there is a legal or practical distinction between the terms \"stay-at-home\" and \"shelter-in-place\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus in Oklahoma: More than a quarter of Oklahoma residents firmly under shelter-in-place orders|first=Kayla|last=Branch|work=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5658868/coronavirus-in-oklahoma-more-than-a-quarter-of-oklahoma-residents-firmly-under-shelter-in-place-orders}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus in Houston: What's the difference between a stay-at-home order and a shelter-in-place?|first=Gwendolyn|last=Wu|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/coronavirus/article/difference-between-stay-at-home-shelter-in-place-15153029.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Stay-at-home vs shelter-in-place: Here's what they mean|first=Chelsea|last=Tatham|publisher=[[WTSP]]|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/what-is-shelter-in-place-stay-at-home-safer-at-home/67-feb990ee-dc3f-439c-acff-dee258394126}}</ref>\n\n==Orders==\n[[File:Safer at Home Barricade.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A sign at a playground in [[Sheboygan, Wisconsin]] notes the stay-at-home order of [[Governor of Wisconsin|Governor]] [[Tony Evers]] (the noted \"[https://evers.wi.gov/Documents/COVID19/EMO12-SaferAtHome.pdf Emergency Order #12]\") as the reason for closing access to the playground equipment, and the criminal consequences of violating the order.]]\n===Powers===\nIn the United States, the [[United States constitutional law]] gives a [[Police power (United States constitutional law)|police power]] to the states. State governments can use this power within their own state. However, there is no clear authority for either the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] or state governments to impose such a lockdown between states. In term of legality of an order, the government must be able to prove that the order advances a \"compelling government interest\" and the actions are narrow to specifically achieve that goal and they are not unnecessary broad.<ref name=\"stat\">{{cite news |last=Florko |first=Nicholas |title=Explaining a mass quarantine: What does it mean to \u2018shelter in place\u2019? And who has the power to call for it? |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/17/mass-quarantine-lockdown-explainer/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=STAT |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Scopes===\nThe scope of the lockdowns or stay-at-home orders can vary. There is no universal definition of what is deemed essential. Some orders allow residents to come out for outdoor activities. When residents come out of the house, the [[social distancing]] rules are typically applied. Some examples of essential services are banks, gas stations, grocery stores, medical offices, pharmacies, and restaurants (without dining in).<ref name=\"nbcchicago\"/> \n\nIn more restrictive measures in some locations, they require residents to carry paperwork in order to go out to do essential tasks.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Sin\u00e9ad |title=French people ignored officials' warnings to isolate themselves because of the coronavirus. Now they need a form to leave the house. |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-france-requires-form-leave-house-walk-shopping-2020-3 |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> In the most restrictive orders such as in China and Italy, they are considered to amount to [[cordon sanitaire]]s.<ref name=\"stat\"/>\n\n===Effectiveness===\nIn the early days of China's lockdown to combat COVID-19, many{{quantify|date=April 2020}} public-health officials and the World Health Organization praised the efforts in helping to slow  the spread of the disease. However, many{{quantify|date=April 2020}} public-health experts regard the measures as ineffective and unethical, expressing concern about a violation of public trust - which is required in order to have cooperation from the public to make [[social distancing | social-distancing]] measures effective.<ref name=\"stat\"/>\n\n==2020 coronavirus pandemic==\n{{Main|Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n===China===\n{{Main|2020 Hubei lockdowns}}\n\n===Italy===\n{{Main|2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown}}\n\n===India===\n{{See also|Indian local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|2020 India coronavirus lockdown}}\nOn 22 March 2020, the [[Government of India]] decided to completely lockdown 82 districts in 22 states and Union Territories of country where confirmed cases have been reported till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/82-districts-under-lockdown-over-covid-19-what-s-open-and-what-is-shut/story-c1AEMZXuuXN6FvmrAdRvsJ.html |title=82 districts under lockdown over Covid-19: What is shut and where |date=2020-03-23 |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |language=en |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Essential services and commodities were allowed. 80 cities including major cities such as [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]], [[Chennai]], [[Delhi]], [[Mumbai]], [[Pune]] and [[Kolkata]] were also put under lockdown until 31 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-covid-19-80-cities-across-india-go-into-lockdown-till-march-31-what-it-means-2198894 |title=Coronavirus: 80 Cities Across India Go Into Lockdown Till March 31. What It Means |website=NDTV.com |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The country entered complete lockdown from 25 March 2020 for 21 days amid increase in number of cases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52024239|title=India's 1.3bn population told to stay at home|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Malaysia===\n{{Main|2020 Malaysia movement control order}}\n\n===New Zealand===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\nOn 23 March 2020, Prime Minister [[Jacinda Ardern]] raised New Zealand's COVID-19 alert level to three and announced the closure of all schools beginning on that day. The Government also announced that they would raise the national alert level to four at 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on 25 March 2020, which would lead to a nationwide lockdown. While all sporting matches and events as well as non-essential services such as pools, bars, cafes, restaurants, playgrounds are required to close in 48 hours, essential services such as supermarkets, petrol stations, and health services will remain open.<ref>{{cite news |last=Palmer |first=Scott |title=Coronavirus: New Zealand goes to COVID-19 alert level 3 |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-new-zealand-goes-to-covid-19-alert-level-3.html |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Newshub]] |date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323055338/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-new-zealand-goes-to-covid-19-alert-level-3.html |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Roy |first=Eleanor |title='Kiwis \u2013 go home': New Zealand to go into month-long lockdown to fight coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/kiwis-go-home-new-zealand-to-go-into-month-long-lockdown-to-fight-coronavirus |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323025021/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/kiwis-go-home-new-zealand-to-go-into-month-long-lockdown-to-fight-coronavirus |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus live updates in NZ and around the world on 23 March |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/412361/coronavirus-live-updates-in-nz-and-around-the-world-on-23-march |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323000431/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/412361/coronavirus-live-updates-in-nz-and-around-the-world-on-23-march |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines===\n{{Main|2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine}}\n\n===Singapore===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore}}\nOn 3 April 2020, Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] announced that Singapore will be strengthening its restrictions in view of evidence of growing spread within the community and the risk of asymptomatic spread from 7 April to 4 May. All non-essential services such as retail, recreation, sports and attractions, as well as schools are required to close during this period. Essential services such as supermarkets, some eateries, petrol kiosks, logistics, basic haircuts, public transport, facilities management, management of key IT infrastructures and health services will remain open with stringent restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/circuit-breaker-to-minimise-further-spread-of-covid-19|title=Circuit breaker to minimise spread of COVID-19|date=2020-04-03|work=Ministry of Health, Singapore|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-SG}}</ref>These measures include the prohibition of dining-in in eateries, suspending and/or reducing the frequency of bus and MRT services, and requiring almost all commercial and educational services to [[telecommuting|work]] and study from home respectively. All mid-year exams in primary, secondary schools and junior colleges, as well as graduation ceremonies during this period are cancelled. Military in-camp training for NSmen are also postponed till further notice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-03/singapore-pm-says-more-steps-coming-on-virus-lee-speaks-at-4pm|title=Singapore to close schools, most workplaces with rising virus cases|date=2020-04-03|work=Bloomberg|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\nAt 8:30&nbsp;p.m. on 23 March 2020, Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] announced a stay-at-home order effective immediately. All non-essential shops and services were ordered to close, and police were given discretion to break up gatherings of more than two people. Johnson stated that the stay-at-home order will be reviewed after three weeks.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52012432 |title=Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM |date=2020-03-23 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=2020-03-23 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n{{main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA stay-at-home order county map.svg|thumb|right|States, territories, and counties that issued a stay-at-home order:\n{{legend|#045a8d|Came into effect before 22 March}}\n{{legend|#2b8cbe|Came into effect before 29 March}}\n{{legend|#74a9cf|Came into effect before 5 April}}\n{{legend|#bdc9e1|Came into effect before 12 April}}\n'''[[Commons:Data:Stay-at-home orders in the United States.map|Full map including municipalities]]''']]\n\nStay-at-home orders in the United States have come from several states and a large number of local jurisdictions, sometimes leading to conflicts between different levels of government and a patchwork of inconsistent dates and rules.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Cases, Concentrated on the Coasts, Now Threaten America\u2019s Middle |first=Julie |last=Bosman |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2020-03-27 |access-date=2020-03-27 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/coronavirus-usa-midwest-south.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Analysis: Coronavirus and local control in Texas|first=Ross|last=Ramsey|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/27/coronavirus-and-local-control-texas/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Is Cabela's an \"essential\" business? Texas counties differ on who should work during shelter in place|first=Sami|last=Sparber|work=The Texas Tribune|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/26/whats-essential-texas-business-coronavirus-crisis-its-not-clear/}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2020, Puerto Rico governor [[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]] signed an [[executive order]] to order all citizens to stay home starting at 9&nbsp;p.m. with exceptions in limited circumstances between 5&nbsp;a.m. and 9&nbsp;p.m. Governmental operations and non-essential businesses were to be closed until 30 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Administrative Bulletin No.: OE-2020-023 |url=https://basecero.ogp.pr.gov/apex/apex_util.get_blob?s=3089088855514&a=161&c=112063554695324788&p=15&k1=4725&k2=&ck=D6tlniXHJx7rJWaWeq2EajrOBWVcTiOxSJhaIRIG10IWAJAhKB8_IXXQbMFDQbvsOxueRM1NBfO4Yf30a2Y_Nw&rt=IR |publisher=[[Government of Puerto Rico]] |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first order within the states was simultaneously imposed by health authorities in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] ([[Alameda County, California|Alameda]], [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa]], [[Marin County, California|Marin]], [[San Mateo, California|San Mateo]], and [[Santa Clara County, California|Santa Clara]] counties and the cities of [[San Francisco]] and [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]]) effective 17 March 2020, affecting nearly 6.7 million people.<ref name=\"sfchronicle\"/> Other cities and counties followed suit over the next two days, until [[Gavin Newsom]], the governor of California, issued a statewide order effective 19 March 2020.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite news |title=What's a \u2018Shelter in Place\u2019 Order, and Who\u2019s Affected? |url=https://www.wired.com/story/whats-shelter-place-order-whos-affected/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, New York governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] announced the statewide stay-at-home order with a mandate that 100% of non-essential workforce to be conducted as [[working from home]] effective 22 March.<ref name=\"npr\"/> Illinois governor [[J. B. Pritzker]] followed that lead on the same day with a statewide order which would go into effect on 21 March at 5 p.m.<ref name=\"tribune\"/> [[Ned Lamont]], the governor of Connecticut, signed an executive order called \"Stay Safe, Stay At Home\" to take effect statewide on 23 March at 8 p.m. \n\nOn 21 March 2020, New Jersey governor [[Phil Murphy]] announced a statewide stay-at-home order effective at 9 p.m. on the same day.<ref>{{cite news |last=Perez |first=Matt |title=New Jersey Ordered To Stay-At-Home, Joining California, Illinois And Others |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mattperez/2020/03/21/new-jersey-ordered-to-stay-at-home-joining-california-illinois-and-others/#6978eba46e26 |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Forbes]] |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2020, Ohio governor [[Mike DeWine]] and [[Ohio Department of Health]] director [[Amy Acton]] issued a statewide stay-at-home order effective 23 March.<ref name=\"Enquirer Borchardt\">{{cite news |title=Ohio Gov. DeWine orders Ohioans to shelter in place, nonessential business, most daycares to close |first=Jackie |last=Borchardt |work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |date=2020-03-22 |access-date=2020-03-22 |url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/22/coronavirus-ohio-gov-mike-dewine-sunday-update-states-response/2894473001/ |quote=Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine said in his update Sunday Dr. Amy Acton is ordering a stay at home order or shelter in place order for all Ohioans. The order is in effect beginning midnight Monday and is in effect through April 6.}}</ref> In the afternoon, the Louisiana governor [[John Bel Edwards]] announced a statewide stay-at-home order in a press conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Karlin |first=Sam |title=Louisiana issues statewide stay-at-home order to combat coronavirus spread |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/coronavirus/article_922869e8-6c6d-11ea-aeee-6b6fd5e8f4bd.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]] |location=Baton Rouge, Louisiana |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Delaware governor [[John Carney (politician)|John Carney]] followed suit with a stay-at-home order for his state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stay-at-home order issued in Delaware starting Tuesday |url=https://apnews.com/0692f5c364f07045809a734775e1b260 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=22 March 2020 |location=Wilmington |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2020, several state governors announced their statewide stay-at-home order:\n\n* Massachusetts governor [[Charlie Baker]] ordered non-essential businesses to close in-person operations effective 24 March until 7 April and directed the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]] to issue a stay-at-home advisory.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Governor Charlie Baker Orders All Non-Essential Businesses To Cease In Person Operation, Directs the Department of Public Health to Issue Stay at Home Advisory For Two Weeks |publisher=[[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]] |date=2020-03-23 |access-date=2020-03-24 |url=https://www.mass.gov/news/governor-charlie-baker-orders-all-non-essential-businesses-to-cease-in-person-operation}}</ref>\n* Michigan governor [[Gretchen Whitmer]] announced her statewide executive order to stay-at-home at 11:00 am for all non-essential businesses effective 24 March until 13 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Michigan residents ordered to stay at home to slow COVID-19 spread |url=https://www.woodtv.com/health/coronavirus/official-gov-whitmer-to-issue-stay-at-home-order-to-combat-covid-19/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=WOOD TV |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n* Indiana governor [[Eric Holcomb]] announced statewide stay-at-home order effective 25 March until 7 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Indiana Gov. Eric Holcomb Issues \u2018Stay-at-Home\u2019 Order Amid Coronavirus Pandemic |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/coronavirus/indiana-gov-eric-holcomb-issues-stay-at-home-order-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/2242781/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[NBC Chicago]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n* West Virginia governor [[Jim Justice]] ordered non-essential businesses to be closed immediately, and stay-at-home order effective at 8&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Justice orders shutdown of non-essential businesses in West Virginia; first community-transmitted case has been confirmed |url=https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/gov-justice-orders-shutdown-of-non-essential-businesses-in-west/article_24910f48-6d21-11ea-8518-3fbb944964d3.html |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=West Virginia's News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n* After growing calls from local officials on Sunday, Oregon governor [[Kate Brown]] issued a stay-at-home order on Monday effective immediately with class C [[misdemeanor]] charges for violators.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gunderson |first=Laura |title=Oregon stay at home order: Where can I go? |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-stay-at-home-order-where-can-i-go.html |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[The Oregonian]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n* New Mexico governor [[Michelle Lujan Grisham]] announced a statewide stay-at-home order that requires 100% of non-essential business workforce to work from home effective 24 March until 10 April.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Jim |title=New Mexico\u2019s governor issues stay-at-home order due to coronavirus outbreak |url=https://kvia.com/news/new-mexico/2020/03/23/new-mexicos-governor-to-issue-stay-at-home-order-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=KVIA |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Washington governor [[Jay Inslee]] signed a statewide stay-at-home proclamation and ordered to close non-essential businesses effective 25 March for two weeks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Inslee issues \u2018stay at home\u2019 proclamation for Washington state |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1782819/inslee-washington-stay-at-home-order/? |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=MYNorthwest |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Hawaii governor [[David Ige]] issued a statewide stay-at-home order effective 25 March which was similar to the orders that were previously issued for Maui and Honolulu counties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Uechi |first=Colleen |title=Ige takes \u2018stay at home\u2019 mandate statewide |url=https://www.mauinews.com/news/local-news/2020/03/ige-takes-stay-at-home-mandate-statewide/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=[[The Maui News]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=IN FULL: Read the governor\u2019s stay-at-home emergency proclamation |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2020/03/24/full-read-governors-stay-at-home-emergency-proclamation/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=[[Hawaii News Now]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Wisconsin governor [[Tony Evers]] issued a statewide stay-at-home order to close all non-essential businesses and ordered no gatherings of any size effective 25 March until 24 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wisconsin Governor Issues Order Closing Businesses |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/coronavirus/wisconsin-governor-issues-order-closing-businesses/2243503/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=[[NBC Chicago]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Vermont governor [[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]] signed a stay-at-home order and directed closure of in-person operations of non-essential businesses effective 25 March until 15 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scott issues 'stay at home' order |url=https://www.wcax.com/content/news/Scott-issues-stay-at-home-order-569070201.html |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=WCAX |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, Idaho governor [[Brad Little]] and Minnesota governor [[Tim Walz]] issued stay-at-home orders for their respective states.<ref>{{cite newspaper |last=Bierschbach |first=Briana |title=Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz: 'Stay at home' |url=https://www.startribune.com/gov-tim-walz-tells-minnesotans-stay-home-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/569095212/ |newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] |access-date=25 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ridler |first=Keith |title=Idaho Gov. Brad Little issues statewide stay-at-home order |url=https://www.tri-cityherald.com/news/business/health-care/article241496151.html |work=[[Tri-City Herald]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=25 March 2020 |location=Boise |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>  Colorado Govenor [[Jared Polis]] puts the state of Colorado in complete lock-down, with a stay at home order. This started on Thursday the 26th at 6&nbsp;a.m. and lasts through 11 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/25/polis-announces-statewide-stay-at-home-order/ |title=Polis Issues Colorado Stay-at-Home Order: \u2018Now Is Not The Time To Die\u2019 |website=Colorado Public Radio}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Georgia governor [[Brian Kemp]] issued stay-at-home order effective Friday, April 3,  2020, until Monday, April 13, 2020. <ref>{{cite executive order |number=04.02.20.01 |url=https://gov.georgia.gov/document/2020-executive-order/04022001/download |date= {{date|2020-04-02|mdy}} |language=English |post=Governor of Georgia |accessdate={{date|2020-04-03|mdy}}}}</ref> It overrules any local stay-at-home restrictions previously in place, and instructs residents to stay  at home unless they're conducting \"essential services,\" meaning either traveling to and from jobs or other exceptions, including buying groceries; purchasing medical equipment; going out to exercise; and visiting medical facilities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kemp details Georgia\u2019s statewide shelter in place order |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/politics/kemp-details-georgia-shelter-place-order/hc3ETUjzBedtWW1LoJHTIP/ |access-date=3 April 2020 |work=AJC |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>  The same day, Dr. [[Anthony Fauci]] publicly questions why all states are not under stay-at-home orders.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/fauci-i-don-t-understand-why-all-states-are-not-n1175841</ref><ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/03/i-just-dont-understand-why-were-not-doing-that-fauci-calls-nationwide-stay-at-home-despite-trumps-resistance</ref>\n\n====Indian nations====\nOn 20 March 2020, [[Navajo Nation]] announced that it broadened the stay-at-home order to cover the entire [[Indian reservation|reservation]], which is the largest reservation in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tribes taking steps in attempt to slow outbreak's spread |url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/mar/22/tribes-taking-steps-in-attempt-to-slow-/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2020, [[Yakama Nation]] announced its \"Stay Home, Stay Healthy\" order.<ref>{{cite web |title=Public Safety Order No. 1 |url=http://www.yakamanation-nsn.gov/stay_home_stay_healthy.pdf |publisher=The Yakama Nation Main Agency Offices |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Disaster management]]\n[[Category:Domestic responses]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{Globalize|1=article|2=United States|date=March 2020}}\n{{Redirect-distinguish|Shelter-in-place order|Shelter in place}}\n{{Short description|Quarantine strategy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020|cs1-dates=y}}\nA '''stay-at-home order''' (North America) or a '''movement control order''' (Southeast Asia) is an order from an authority to restrict movements of population as a mass [[quarantine]] strategy for suppressing or mitigating an [[epidemic]] or [[pandemic]] by ordering residents to stay home except for essential tasks or going to work in essential businesses. In many cases, outdoor activities are allowed. Nonessential businesses are either closed or changed to be [[working from home]].<ref name=\"nbcchicago\">{{cite news |title=What You Can and Cannot Do During a Stay-at-Home or Shelter-in-Place Order |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/what-you-can-and-cannot-do-during-a-stay-at-home-or-shelter-in-place-order/2241024/ |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=NBC Chicago |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> In some regions, it has been implemented as a round-the-clock [[curfew]]<ref>{{cite news |title=City of Birmingham under Shelter in Place in order |publisher=[[WBRC]]|date=March 24, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |url=https://www.wsfa.com/2020/03/24/birminghams-mayor-proposes-ordinance-shelter-place-during-coronavirus-outbreak/}}</ref> or called a '''shelter-in-place order''',<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus stay-at-home and shelter-in-place orders, by state|work=[[USA Today]]|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/03/30/coronavirus-stay-home-shelter-in-place-orders-by-state/5092413002/}}</ref> but it is not to be confused with a [[shelter in place]] situation.<ref>{{cite news|title=In pandemic, word definitions shift and new lexicon emerges|first=Matt|last=Sedensky|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=AP News|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020|url=https://apnews.com/d7b3035038a786d4aaed35e9b672a9d2}}</ref> Similar measures have been used around the world, but the term '''lockdown''' is used instead.<ref name=\"Kottasov\u00e1\">{{cite news |last=Kottasov\u00e1 |first=Ivana |title=Coronavirus lockdowns: 24 hours of confusion around the world |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/health/restrictions-lockdowns-confusion-coronavirus-intl/index.html |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Some officials have a concern that the word lockdown may send a wrong message for people to incorrectly think that it includes door-to-door searching for infected people to be forced into quarantines similar to the [[Wuhan lockdown]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Sedensky |first=Matt |title=In pandemic, word definitions shift and new lexicon emerges |url=https://apnews.com/d7b3035038a786d4aaed35e9b672a9d2 |access-date=24 March 2020 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n{{See also|Shelter in place|Lockdown}}\nThe term ''[[lockdown]]'' was used by the media and the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) to describe the action taken in January 2020 by the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|government of China]] to restrict movements of people in order to control the outbreak of [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|Wuhan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wuhan lockdown 'unprecedented', shows commitment to contain virus: WHO representative in China |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-who-idUSKBN1ZM1G9 |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> When Italian authorities imposed [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|a strict quarantine order]] in the northern part of the country, the media also used the term lockdown, which was used for [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|Spain]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]], as well as other countries around the world.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Venice Carnival closes as Italy imposes lockdown |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51602007 |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=[[BBC]] |date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Sam |title=Spain orders nationwide lockdown to battle coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/14/spain-government-set-to-order-nationwide-coronavirus-lockdown |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mcardle |first=Mairead |title=France Announces Two-Week Lockdown, Orders Residents to Stay Home |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/news/coronavirus-pandemic-france-announces-two-week-lockdown-orders-residents-to-stay-home/ |access-date=21 March 2020 |work=[[National Review]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Secon |first1=Holly |last2=Frias |first2=Lauren |last3=McFall-Johnsen |first3=Morgan |title=A running list of countries that are on lockdown because of the coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/countries-on-lockdown-coronavirus-italy-2020-3 |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Although it is not a technical term in [[public health]] or laws, the media continued to use ''lockdown'' to describe the actions taken by these governments.<ref>{{cite news |last=Resnick |first=Brian |title=Italy and China used lockdowns to slow the coronavirus. Could we? |url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2020/3/10/21171464/coronavirus-us-lockdown-travel-restriction-italy |access-date=25 March 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media, LLC.]] |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> As the lockdowns were expanded to other countries, there was a shift in the definitions. Measures are less restrictive and other terms emerged in attempts to differentiate from the most restrictive measure in China.<ref name=Kottasov\u00e1/>\n\n[[File:Loyalsock Volunteer Fire Co COVID-19 warning sign.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Many jurisdictions in the United States have referred to their stay-at-home orders by the slogan \"Stay home, stay safe.\"]]\n\nWhen the authorities in [[San Francisco Bay Area]] issued an order in March 2020 for residents to stay home to control the outbreak of COVID-19, they called it a ''shelter-in-place order''.<ref name=sfchronicle>{{cite news |last=Ravani |first=Sarah |title=Bay Area coronavirus decision: Behind the scenes of nation\u2019s first shelter-in-place order |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Bay-Area-coronavirus-decision-Behind-the-scenes-15148425.php |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> People were not familiar with it as the term ''[[shelter in place]]'' had been used in other emergency situations such as an [[active shooter]] which would require seeking a safe place to hide within the same building that the person already occupies until the situation is resolved.<ref>{{cite news |last=Waldrop |first=Theresa |title=Self-isolation, quarantine and California's stay-at-home order: What the terms mean and how they differ |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/19/health/shelter-in-place-isolation-quarantine-definition/index.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> This caused confusion to the residents under the order on what exactly they are supposed to do.<ref>{{cite news |last=Singal |first=Jesse |title=Stop Using the Term \u2018Shelter in Place\u2019 for the Coronavirus Crisis |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/shelter-in-place-in-coronavirus-crisis-what-does-it-mean.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Intelligencer (website)|Intelligencer]] |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Gavin Newsom|Governor Gavin Newsom]] announced the state-wide order for California which would supersede the Bay Area's order, he used the term ''stay-at-home order'' instead.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tolan |first=Casey |title=Coronavirus: Newsom\u2019s stay-at-home order differs from the Bay Area\u2019s shelter-in-place rules. Now what happens? |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2020/03/20/coronavirus-california-stay-home-order-local-bay-area-covid-19-rules/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[The Mercury News]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Other US states started using the new term when they announced their statewide order.<ref name=npr>{{cite news |title=New York, Illinois Governors Issue Stay At Home Orders, Following California's Lead |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/20/818952589/coronavirus-n-y-gov-cuomo-says-100-of-workforce-must-stay-home |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> In a press conference, [[Andrew Cuomo|Governor Andrew Cuomo]] of New York criticized anyone using the term shelter in place for his stay-at-home order as it would invoke panic due to its association with active shooting situations or [[nuclear war]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Corey |first=Rebecca |title=Shelter in place, stay at home, quarantine: What do coronavirus restrictions mean? |url=https://news.yahoo.com/shelter-in-place-stay-at-home-quarantine-what-do-coronavirus-restrictions-mean-145017819.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Yahoo News]] |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Lockdowns in the United States===\nIn the United States, the term ''lockdown'' has been widely used in emergency preparedness. A lockdown procedure requires immediate actions in hiding and locking all doors. Additional actions may be taken such as turning off lights and staying away from windows.<ref>{{cite web |title=Emergency Lockdown Planning Considerations |url=https://emilms.fema.gov/IS360/groups/217.html |publisher=[[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Guide for Developing High-Quality School Emergency Operations Plans |date=2013 |publisher=[[U.S. Department of Education]] |url=https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/20130726-1922-25045-3850/rems_k_12_guide.pdf |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Students in all grade levels around the country participate in lockdown drills on a regular basis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pinsker |first=Joe |title=When Was the Last Time American Children Were So Afraid? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2019/05/lockdown-drill-fear/589090/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=The Atlantic |date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe word ''lockdown'' can also be associated a [[martial law]] to mean that people cannot leave their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hays |first=Holly V. |title=Shelter in place, stay at home, lockdown: What the terms mean |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/health/2020/03/23/shelter-place-stay-home-lockdown-what-terms-mean/2900320001/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Indy Star]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> In an attempt to avoid confusion, [[Lori Lightfoot|Mayor Lori Lightfoot]] of Chicago made a comment about the stay-at-home order of Illinois by trying to differentiate it from a lockdown or a martial law.<ref name=\"tribune\">{{cite news |last=Munks |first=Jamie |title=Gov. Pritzker issued a stay-at-home order. What does that mean? |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/coronavirus/ct-coronavirus-what-is-shelter-in-place-20200320-rvyzf7h24ff5tfnvve5kz6g6b4-story.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen states and counties across the United States issued an order to have residents to remain home, they either called it shelter-in-place order or stay-at-home order. It has been clarified that these orders are not lockdowns because residents are allowed to go in and out of their homes in limited circumstances.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hauck |first=Grace |title=These states are ordering residents to stay home or shelter in place. What does that mean? |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/nation/2020/03/21/coronavirus-lockdown-orders-shelter-place-stay-home-state-list/2891193001/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Courier Journal]] |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Some jurisdictions have determined that there is a legal or practical distinction between the terms \"stay-at-home\" and \"shelter-in-place\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus in Oklahoma: More than a quarter of Oklahoma residents firmly under shelter-in-place orders|first=Kayla|last=Branch|work=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5658868/coronavirus-in-oklahoma-more-than-a-quarter-of-oklahoma-residents-firmly-under-shelter-in-place-orders}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus in Houston: What's the difference between a stay-at-home order and a shelter-in-place?|first=Gwendolyn|last=Wu|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/coronavirus/article/difference-between-stay-at-home-shelter-in-place-15153029.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Stay-at-home vs shelter-in-place: Here's what they mean|first=Chelsea|last=Tatham|publisher=[[WTSP]]|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/what-is-shelter-in-place-stay-at-home-safer-at-home/67-feb990ee-dc3f-439c-acff-dee258394126}}</ref>\n\n==Orders==\n[[File:Safer at Home Barricade.jpg|thumb|right|130px|A sign at a playground in [[Sheboygan, Wisconsin]] notes the stay-at-home order of [[Governor of Wisconsin|Governor]] [[Tony Evers]] (the noted \"[https://evers.wi.gov/Documents/COVID19/EMO12-SaferAtHome.pdf Emergency Order #12]\") as the reason for closing access to the playground equipment, and the criminal consequences of violating the order.]]\n===Powers===\nIn the United States, the [[United States constitutional law]] gives a [[Police power (United States constitutional law)|police power]] to the states. State governments can use this power within their own state. However, there is no clear authority for either the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] or state governments to impose such a lockdown between states. In term of legality of an order, the government must be able to prove that the order advances a \"compelling government interest\" and the actions are narrow to specifically achieve that goal and they are not unnecessary broad.<ref name=\"stat\">{{cite news |last=Florko |first=Nicholas |title=Explaining a mass quarantine: What does it mean to \u2018shelter in place\u2019? And who has the power to call for it? |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/17/mass-quarantine-lockdown-explainer/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=STAT |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Scopes===\nThe scope of the lockdowns or stay-at-home orders can vary. There is no universal definition of what is deemed essential. Some orders allow residents to come out for outdoor activities. When residents come out of the house, the [[social distancing]] rules are typically applied. Some examples of essential services are banks, gas stations, grocery stores, medical offices, pharmacies, and restaurants (without dining in).<ref name=\"nbcchicago\"/> \n\nIn more restrictive measures in some locations, they require residents to carry paperwork in order to go out to do essential tasks.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Sin\u00e9ad |title=French people ignored officials' warnings to isolate themselves because of the coronavirus. Now they need a form to leave the house. |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-france-requires-form-leave-house-walk-shopping-2020-3 |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> In the most restrictive orders such as in China and Italy, they are considered to amount to [[cordon sanitaire]]s.<ref name=\"stat\"/>\n\n===Effectiveness===\nIn the early days of China's lockdown to combat COVID-19, many{{quantify|date=April 2020}} public-health officials and the World Health Organization praised the efforts in helping to slow  the spread of the disease. However, many{{quantify|date=April 2020}} public-health experts regard the measures as ineffective and unethical, expressing concern about a violation of public trust - which is required in order to have cooperation from the public to make [[social distancing | social-distancing]] measures effective.<ref name=\"stat\"/>\n\n==2020 coronavirus pandemic==\n{{Main|Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n===China===\n{{Main|2020 Hubei lockdowns}}\n\n===Italy===\n{{Main|2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown}}\n\n===India===\n{{See also|Indian local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|2020 India coronavirus lockdown}}\nOn 22 March 2020, the [[Government of India]] decided to completely lockdown 82 districts in 22 states and Union Territories of country where confirmed cases have been reported till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/82-districts-under-lockdown-over-covid-19-what-s-open-and-what-is-shut/story-c1AEMZXuuXN6FvmrAdRvsJ.html |title=82 districts under lockdown over Covid-19: What is shut and where |date=2020-03-23 |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |language=en |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Essential services and commodities were allowed. 80 cities including major cities such as [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]], [[Chennai]], [[Delhi]], [[Mumbai]], [[Pune]] and [[Kolkata]] were also put under lockdown until 31 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-covid-19-80-cities-across-india-go-into-lockdown-till-march-31-what-it-means-2198894 |title=Coronavirus: 80 Cities Across India Go Into Lockdown Till March 31. What It Means |website=NDTV.com |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The country entered complete lockdown from 25 March 2020 for 21 days amid increase in number of cases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52024239|title=India's 1.3bn population told to stay at home|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Malaysia===\n{{Main|2020 Malaysia movement control order}}\n\n===New Zealand===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\nOn 23 March 2020, Prime Minister [[Jacinda Ardern]] raised New Zealand's COVID-19 alert level to three and announced the closure of all schools beginning on that day. The Government also announced that they would raise the national alert level to four at 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on 25 March 2020, which would lead to a nationwide lockdown. While all sporting matches and events as well as non-essential services such as pools, bars, cafes, restaurants, playgrounds are required to close in 48 hours, essential services such as supermarkets, petrol stations, and health services will remain open.<ref>{{cite news |last=Palmer |first=Scott |title=Coronavirus: New Zealand goes to COVID-19 alert level 3 |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-new-zealand-goes-to-covid-19-alert-level-3.html |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Newshub]] |date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323055338/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-new-zealand-goes-to-covid-19-alert-level-3.html |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Roy |first=Eleanor |title='Kiwis \u2013 go home': New Zealand to go into month-long lockdown to fight coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/kiwis-go-home-new-zealand-to-go-into-month-long-lockdown-to-fight-coronavirus |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323025021/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/kiwis-go-home-new-zealand-to-go-into-month-long-lockdown-to-fight-coronavirus |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus live updates in NZ and around the world on 23 March |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/412361/coronavirus-live-updates-in-nz-and-around-the-world-on-23-march |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323000431/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/412361/coronavirus-live-updates-in-nz-and-around-the-world-on-23-march |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines===\n{{Main|2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine}}\n\n===Singapore===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore}}\nOn 3 April 2020, Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] announced that Singapore will be strengthening its restrictions in view of evidence of growing spread within the community and the risk of asymptomatic spread from 7 April to 4 May. All non-essential services such as retail, recreation, sports and attractions, as well as schools are required to close during this period. Essential services such as supermarkets, some eateries, petrol kiosks, logistics, basic haircuts, public transport, facilities management, management of key IT infrastructures and health services will remain open with stringent restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/circuit-breaker-to-minimise-further-spread-of-covid-19|title=Circuit breaker to minimise spread of COVID-19|date=2020-04-03|work=Ministry of Health, Singapore|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-SG}}</ref>These measures include the prohibition of dining-in in eateries, suspending and/or reducing the frequency of bus and MRT services, and requiring almost all commercial and educational services to [[telecommuting|work]] and study from home respectively. All mid-year exams in primary, secondary schools and junior colleges, as well as graduation ceremonies during this period are cancelled. Military in-camp training for NSmen are also postponed till further notice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-03/singapore-pm-says-more-steps-coming-on-virus-lee-speaks-at-4pm|title=Singapore to close schools, most workplaces with rising virus cases|date=2020-04-03|work=Bloomberg|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\nAt 8:30&nbsp;p.m. on 23 March 2020, Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] announced a stay-at-home order effective immediately. All non-essential shops and services were ordered to close, and police were given discretion to break up gatherings of more than two people. Johnson stated that the stay-at-home order will be reviewed after three weeks.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52012432 |title=Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM |date=2020-03-23 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=2020-03-23 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n{{main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA stay-at-home order county map.svg|thumb|right|States, territories, and counties that issued a stay-at-home order:\n{{legend|#045a8d|Came into effect before 22 March}}\n{{legend|#2b8cbe|Came into effect before 29 March}}\n{{legend|#74a9cf|Came into effect before 5 April}}\n{{legend|#bdc9e1|Came into effect before 12 April}}\n'''[[Commons:Data:Stay-at-home orders in the United States.map|Full map including municipalities]]''']]\n\nStay-at-home orders in the United States have come from several states and a large number of local jurisdictions, sometimes leading to conflicts between different levels of government and a patchwork of inconsistent dates and rules.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Cases, Concentrated on the Coasts, Now Threaten America\u2019s Middle |first=Julie |last=Bosman |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2020-03-27 |access-date=2020-03-27 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/coronavirus-usa-midwest-south.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Analysis: Coronavirus and local control in Texas|first=Ross|last=Ramsey|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/27/coronavirus-and-local-control-texas/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Is Cabela's an \"essential\" business? Texas counties differ on who should work during shelter in place|first=Sami|last=Sparber|work=The Texas Tribune|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/26/whats-essential-texas-business-coronavirus-crisis-its-not-clear/}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2020, Puerto Rico governor [[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]] signed an [[executive order]] to order all citizens to stay home starting at 9&nbsp;p.m. with exceptions in limited circumstances between 5&nbsp;a.m. and 9&nbsp;p.m. Governmental operations and non-essential businesses were to be closed until 30 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Administrative Bulletin No.: OE-2020-023 |url=https://basecero.ogp.pr.gov/apex/apex_util.get_blob?s=3089088855514&a=161&c=112063554695324788&p=15&k1=4725&k2=&ck=D6tlniXHJx7rJWaWeq2EajrOBWVcTiOxSJhaIRIG10IWAJAhKB8_IXXQbMFDQbvsOxueRM1NBfO4Yf30a2Y_Nw&rt=IR |publisher=[[Government of Puerto Rico]] |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first order within the states was simultaneously imposed by health authorities in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] ([[Alameda County, California|Alameda]], [[Contra Costa County, California|Contra Costa]], [[Marin County, California|Marin]], [[San Mateo, California|San Mateo]], and [[Santa Clara County, California|Santa Clara]] counties and the cities of [[San Francisco]] and [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]]) effective 17 March 2020, affecting nearly 6.7 million people.<ref name=\"sfchronicle\"/> Other cities and counties followed suit over the next two days, until [[Gavin Newsom]], the governor of California, issued a statewide order effective 19 March 2020.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite news |title=What's a \u2018Shelter in Place\u2019 Order, and Who\u2019s Affected? |url=https://www.wired.com/story/whats-shelter-place-order-whos-affected/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, New York governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] announced the statewide stay-at-home order with a mandate that 100% of non-essential workforce to be conducted as [[working from home]] effective 22 March.<ref name=\"npr\"/> Illinois governor [[J. B. Pritzker]] followed that lead on the same day with a statewide order which would go into effect on 21 March at 5 p.m.<ref name=\"tribune\"/> [[Ned Lamont]], the governor of Connecticut, signed an executive order called \"Stay Safe, Stay At Home\" to take effect statewide on 23 March at 8 p.m. \n\nOn 21 March 2020, New Jersey governor [[Phil Murphy]] announced a statewide stay-at-home order effective at 9 p.m. on the same day.<ref>{{cite news |last=Perez |first=Matt |title=New Jersey Ordered To Stay-At-Home, Joining California, Illinois And Others |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mattperez/2020/03/21/new-jersey-ordered-to-stay-at-home-joining-california-illinois-and-others/#6978eba46e26 |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Forbes]] |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2020, Ohio governor [[Mike DeWine]] and [[Ohio Department of Health]] director [[Amy Acton]] issued a statewide stay-at-home order effective 23 March.<ref name=\"Enquirer Borchardt\">{{cite news |title=Ohio Gov. DeWine orders Ohioans to shelter in place, nonessential business, most daycares to close |first=Jackie |last=Borchardt |work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |date=2020-03-22 |access-date=2020-03-22 |url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/22/coronavirus-ohio-gov-mike-dewine-sunday-update-states-response/2894473001/ |quote=Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine said in his update Sunday Dr. Amy Acton is ordering a stay at home order or shelter in place order for all Ohioans. The order is in effect beginning midnight Monday and is in effect through April 6.}}</ref> In the afternoon, the Louisiana governor [[John Bel Edwards]] announced a statewide stay-at-home order in a press conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Karlin |first=Sam |title=Louisiana issues statewide stay-at-home order to combat coronavirus spread |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/coronavirus/article_922869e8-6c6d-11ea-aeee-6b6fd5e8f4bd.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]] |location=Baton Rouge, Louisiana |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Delaware governor [[John Carney (politician)|John Carney]] followed suit with a stay-at-home order for his state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stay-at-home order issued in Delaware starting Tuesday |url=https://apnews.com/0692f5c364f07045809a734775e1b260 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=22 March 2020 |location=Wilmington |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2020, several state governors announced their statewide stay-at-home order:\n\n* Massachusetts governor [[Charlie Baker]] ordered non-essential businesses to close in-person operations effective 24 March until 7 April and directed the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]] to issue a stay-at-home advisory.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Governor Charlie Baker Orders All Non-Essential Businesses To Cease In Person Operation, Directs the Department of Public Health to Issue Stay at Home Advisory For Two Weeks |publisher=[[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]] |date=2020-03-23 |access-date=2020-03-24 |url=https://www.mass.gov/news/governor-charlie-baker-orders-all-non-essential-businesses-to-cease-in-person-operation}}</ref>\n* Michigan governor [[Gretchen Whitmer]] announced her statewide executive order to stay-at-home at 11:00 am for all non-essential businesses effective 24 March until 13 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Michigan residents ordered to stay at home to slow COVID-19 spread |url=https://www.woodtv.com/health/coronavirus/official-gov-whitmer-to-issue-stay-at-home-order-to-combat-covid-19/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=WOOD TV |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n* Indiana governor [[Eric Holcomb]] announced statewide stay-at-home order effective 25 March until 7 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Indiana Gov. Eric Holcomb Issues \u2018Stay-at-Home\u2019 Order Amid Coronavirus Pandemic |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/coronavirus/indiana-gov-eric-holcomb-issues-stay-at-home-order-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/2242781/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[NBC Chicago]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n* West Virginia governor [[Jim Justice]] ordered non-essential businesses to be closed immediately, and stay-at-home order effective at 8&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Justice orders shutdown of non-essential businesses in West Virginia; first community-transmitted case has been confirmed |url=https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/gov-justice-orders-shutdown-of-non-essential-businesses-in-west/article_24910f48-6d21-11ea-8518-3fbb944964d3.html |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=West Virginia's News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n* After growing calls from local officials on Sunday, Oregon governor [[Kate Brown]] issued a stay-at-home order on Monday effective immediately with class C [[misdemeanor]] charges for violators.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gunderson |first=Laura |title=Oregon stay at home order: Where can I go? |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-stay-at-home-order-where-can-i-go.html |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=[[The Oregonian]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n* New Mexico governor [[Michelle Lujan Grisham]] announced a statewide stay-at-home order that requires 100% of non-essential business workforce to work from home effective 24 March until 10 April.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Jim |title=New Mexico\u2019s governor issues stay-at-home order due to coronavirus outbreak |url=https://kvia.com/news/new-mexico/2020/03/23/new-mexicos-governor-to-issue-stay-at-home-order-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=KVIA |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Washington governor [[Jay Inslee]] signed a statewide stay-at-home proclamation and ordered to close non-essential businesses effective 25 March for two weeks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Inslee issues \u2018stay at home\u2019 proclamation for Washington state |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1782819/inslee-washington-stay-at-home-order/? |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=MYNorthwest |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Hawaii governor [[David Ige]] issued a statewide stay-at-home order effective 25 March which was similar to the orders that were previously issued for Maui and Honolulu counties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Uechi |first=Colleen |title=Ige takes \u2018stay at home\u2019 mandate statewide |url=https://www.mauinews.com/news/local-news/2020/03/ige-takes-stay-at-home-mandate-statewide/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=[[The Maui News]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=IN FULL: Read the governor\u2019s stay-at-home emergency proclamation |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2020/03/24/full-read-governors-stay-at-home-emergency-proclamation/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=[[Hawaii News Now]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Wisconsin governor [[Tony Evers]] issued a statewide stay-at-home order to close all non-essential businesses and ordered no gatherings of any size effective 25 March until 24 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wisconsin Governor Issues Order Closing Businesses |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/coronavirus/wisconsin-governor-issues-order-closing-businesses/2243503/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=[[NBC Chicago]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Vermont governor [[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]] signed a stay-at-home order and directed closure of in-person operations of non-essential businesses effective 25 March until 15 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scott issues 'stay at home' order |url=https://www.wcax.com/content/news/Scott-issues-stay-at-home-order-569070201.html |access-date=24 March 2020 |work=WCAX |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, Idaho governor [[Brad Little]] and Minnesota governor [[Tim Walz]] issued stay-at-home orders for their respective states.<ref>{{cite newspaper |last=Bierschbach |first=Briana |title=Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz: 'Stay at home' |url=https://www.startribune.com/gov-tim-walz-tells-minnesotans-stay-home-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/569095212/ |newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] |access-date=25 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ridler |first=Keith |title=Idaho Gov. Brad Little issues statewide stay-at-home order |url=https://www.tri-cityherald.com/news/business/health-care/article241496151.html |work=[[Tri-City Herald]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=25 March 2020 |location=Boise |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>  Colorado Govenor [[Jared Polis]] puts the state of Colorado in complete lock-down, with a stay at home order. This started on Thursday the 26th at 6&nbsp;a.m. and lasts through 11 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/25/polis-announces-statewide-stay-at-home-order/ |title=Polis Issues Colorado Stay-at-Home Order: \u2018Now Is Not The Time To Die\u2019 |website=Colorado Public Radio}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Georgia governor [[Brian Kemp]] issued stay-at-home order effective Friday, April 3,  2020, until Monday, April 13, 2020. <ref>{{cite executive order |number=04.02.20.01 |url=https://gov.georgia.gov/document/2020-executive-order/04022001/download |date= {{date|2020-04-02|mdy}} |language=English |post=Governor of Georgia |accessdate={{date|2020-04-03|mdy}}}}</ref> It overrules any local stay-at-home restrictions previously in place, and instructs residents to stay  at home unless they're conducting \"essential services,\" meaning either traveling to and from jobs or other exceptions, including buying groceries; purchasing medical equipment; going out to exercise; and visiting medical facilities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kemp details Georgia\u2019s statewide shelter in place order |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/politics/kemp-details-georgia-shelter-place-order/hc3ETUjzBedtWW1LoJHTIP/ |access-date=3 April 2020 |work=AJC |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>  The same day, Dr. [[Anthony Fauci]] publicly questions why all states are not under stay-at-home orders.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/fauci-i-don-t-understand-why-all-states-are-not-n1175841</ref><ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/03/i-just-dont-understand-why-were-not-doing-that-fauci-calls-nationwide-stay-at-home-despite-trumps-resistance</ref>\n\n====Indian nations====\nOn 20 March 2020, [[Navajo Nation]] announced that it broadened the stay-at-home order to cover the entire [[Indian reservation|reservation]], which is the largest reservation in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tribes taking steps in attempt to slow outbreak's spread |url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/mar/22/tribes-taking-steps-in-attempt-to-slow-/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |work=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2020, [[Yakama Nation]] announced its \"Stay Home, Stay Healthy\" order.<ref>{{cite web |title=Public Safety Order No. 1 |url=http://www.yakamanation-nsn.gov/stay_home_stay_healthy.pdf |publisher=The Yakama Nation Main Agency Offices |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Disaster management]]\n[[Category:Domestic responses]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Mrschimpf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrders", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stay-at-home_order"}
{"title_page": "Mangere Island", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Mangere Island\n| local_name      = ''M\u0101ngere'' (''[[Moriori language|Moriori]]/[[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]]'')\n| image_name       = Mangere.jpg\n| image_caption    = Mangere Island (left) and Little Mangere (right)\n| map_image        = Chatham-Islands map topo en.svg\n| map_caption      = Map showing location of Mangere Island\n| nickname         =\n| location         =\n| coordinates      = {{coord|-44.2695|-176.2945|region:NZ_type:isle|}}\n| archipelago      = [[Chatham Islands]]\n| total_islands    =\n| major_islands    =\n| area_km2         = 1.13\n| length_km        =\n| width_km         =\n| highest_mount    = [[Whakapa]]\n| elevation_m      = 292\n| population       = 0\n| population_as_of =\n| density_km2      =\n| ethnic_groups    =\n| country          = [[New Zealand]]\n| additional_info  =\n}}\n'''Mangere Island''' is part of the [[Chatham Islands]] archipelago, located about {{convert|800|km|mi}} east of [[New Zealand|New Zealand's]] [[South Island]] and has an area of {{convert|113|ha|acre|0}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://data.linz.govt.nz/layer/53564-protected-areas/data/91418/|title=Data Table - Protected Areas - LINZ Data Service (recorded area 112.9073 ha)|publisher=[[Land Information New Zealand]]|accessdate=2019-09-03}}</ref> The island lies off the west coast of [[Pitt Island]], {{convert|45|km|mi|0}} south-east of the main settlement in the Chathams, [[Waitangi, Chatham Islands|Waitangi]], on [[Chatham Island]].\n\nMangere and nearby Tapuaenuku ([[Little Mangere Island|Little Mangere]]) are the eroded remains of an ancient [[volcano]] of [[Pliocene]] age. \n\nWhakapa, the island's highest point, is {{convert|292|m|ft|0}} above [[sea level]].\n\nForested until the 1890s, the island was largely cleared for sheep grazing{{Citation needed|date=June 2007}}. [[Rabbit]]s and then [[cat]]s were also introduced but later died out.  Farmed until 1966, the island was then purchased by the New Zealand government and gazetted as a Nature Reserve.<ref name=\"DOC\">[http://www.doc.govt.nz/templates/MultipageDocumentPage.aspx?id=39637 Mangere Island restoration] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930154523/http://www.doc.govt.nz/templates/MultipageDocumentPage.aspx?id=39637 |date=2007-09-30 }} (from the Department of Conservation website)</ref>  The last sheep were removed in 1968 and [[Island restoration|restoration]] of the island started in 1973 and is ongoing.  Several [[endemic]] Chatham Island bird species have since been reintroduced to the island, [[Chatham snipe]] in 1970, [[black robin]]<ref>Attenborough, D. 1998. ''The Life of Birds''. p. 304. BBC {{ISBN|0563-38792-0}}</ref> in 1976, [[Chatham tomtit]] in 1987 and [[shore plover]] in the 1990s.\n\n{{coord|-44.2695|-176.2945|region:NZ_type:isle|display=title}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of islands of New Zealand]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/publications/conservation/land-and-freshwater/land/ecosystem-restoration-on-mainland-nz/island-restoration-case-studies/mangere-island/ DOC Mangere Island case study]\n\n{{Chatham Islands}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Chatham Islands]]\n[[Category:Uninhabited islands of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Island restoration]]\n\n\n{{OutlyingNZ-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Mangere Island\n| local_name      = ''M\u0101ngere'' (''[[Moriori language|Moriori]]/[[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]]'')\n| image_name       = Mangere.jpg\n| image_caption    = Mangere Island (left) and Little Mangere (right)\n| map_image        = Chatham-Islands map topo en.svg\n| map_caption      = Map showing location of Mangere Island\n| nickname         =\n| location         =\n| coordinates      = {{coord|-44.2695|-176.2945|region:NZ_type:isle|}}\n| archipelago      = [[Chatham Islands]]\n| total_islands    =\n| major_islands    =\n| area_km2         = 1.13\n| length_km        =\n| width_km         =\n| highest_mount    = [[Whakapa]]\n| elevation_m      = 292\n| population       = 0\n| population_as_of =\n| density_km2      =\n| ethnic_groups    =\n| country          = [[New Zealand]]\n| additional_info  =\n}}\n'''Mangere Island''' is part of the [[Chatham Islands]] archipelago, located about {{convert|800|km|mi}} east of [[New Zealand|New Zealand's]] [[South Island]] and has an area of {{convert|113|ha|acre|0}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://data.linz.govt.nz/layer/53564-protected-areas/data/91418/|title=Data Table - Protected Areas - LINZ Data Service (recorded area 112.9073 ha)|publisher=[[Land Information New Zealand]]|accessdate=2019-09-03}}</ref> The island lies off the west coast of [[Pitt Island]], {{convert|45|km|mi|0}} south-east of the main settlement in the Chathams, [[Waitangi, Chatham Islands|Waitangi]], on [[Chatham Island]].\n\nMangere and nearby Tapuaenuku ([[Little Mangere Island|Little Mangere]]) are the eroded remains of an ancient [[volcano]] of [[Pliocene]] age. The island's highest point, Whakapa, is {{convert|292|m|ft|0}} above [[sea level]].\n\nForested until the 1890s, the island was largely cleared for sheep grazing{{Citation needed|date=June 2007}}. [[Rabbit]]s and then [[cat]]s were also introduced but later died out.  Farmed until 1966, the island was then purchased by the New Zealand government and gazetted as a Nature Reserve.<ref name=\"DOC\">[http://www.doc.govt.nz/templates/MultipageDocumentPage.aspx?id=39637 Mangere Island restoration] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930154523/http://www.doc.govt.nz/templates/MultipageDocumentPage.aspx?id=39637 |date=2007-09-30 }} (from the Department of Conservation website)</ref>  The last sheep were removed in 1968 and [[Island restoration|restoration]] of the island started in 1973 and is ongoing.  Several [[endemic]] Chatham Island bird species have since been reintroduced to the island, [[Chatham snipe]] in 1970, [[black robin]]<ref>Attenborough, D. 1998. ''The Life of Birds''. p. 304. BBC {{ISBN|0563-38792-0}}</ref> in 1976, [[Chatham tomtit]] in 1987 and [[shore plover]] in the 1990s.\n\n{{coord|-44.2695|-176.2945|region:NZ_type:isle|display=title}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of islands of New Zealand]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/publications/conservation/land-and-freshwater/land/ecosystem-restoration-on-mainland-nz/island-restoration-case-studies/mangere-island/ DOC Mangere Island case study]\n\n{{Chatham Islands}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Chatham Islands]]\n[[Category:Uninhabited islands of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Island restoration]]\n\n\n{{OutlyingNZ-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hugo999", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mangere_Island"}
{"title_page": "Belanglo State Forest", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox forest\n| name          = \n| native_name   = \n| native_lang   =  \n| native_name2  = \n| native_lang2  = \n| photo         = Belanglo State Forest.jpg\n| photo_caption = \n| photo_width   = \n| map           = \n| map_caption   = \n| map_width     = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|-34.531146|150.260049|format=dms}}\n| coords_ref    = \n| county        = [[New South Wales]]\n| region        = [[Southern Highlands (New South Wales)|Southern Highlands]]\n| country       = Australia\n| elevation     = \n| area          =  \n| max_area      = \n| date_max_area = \n| status        = \n| established   = 1919\n| visitation    = \n| visitation_year = \n| events        = \n| authority     = [[Forestry Corporation]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Belanglo State Forest|url=http://www.forestrycorporation.com.au/new/visit/forests/belanglo|website=Forestry Corporation|language=en}}</ref>\n| website       = \n| ecosystem     = \n| classification_WWF = \n| classification_EPA =\n| classification_CEC = \n| disturbance   = \n| forest_cover  = \n| species       = [[Pine]]\n| indicator_plants = \n| lesser_flora  =  \n| fauna         = \n}}\n\n[[File:Belanglo State Forest sign.jpg|thumb|right|400px|This sign at the entrance of the forest advises visitors to \"please be careful\".]]\n\n'''Belanglo State Forest''' is a planted forest, of mainly pine but some native forestry around the edges, in the [[Australia]]n state of [[New South Wales]]; its total area is about 3,800 hectares.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazette.nsw.gov.au/pdfs/2008/2_May-Part_1b.pdf|title=Game and Feral Animal Control Act 2002|page=3037|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326192543/http://www.gazette.nsw.gov.au/pdfs/2008/2_May-Part_1b.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2012}}</ref> The Belanglo State Forest is located south of [[Berrima, New South Wales|Berrima]] in the [[Southern Highlands, New South Wales|Southern Highlands]], three kilometres west of the [[Hume Highway]] between [[Sydney]] and [[Canberra]]. The forest is owned by the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]] and contains some of the earliest [[pine]] plantings in the state. The first [[Pinus radiata|radiata pines]] were planted in this area in 1919.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article222513200 |title=PROCLAMATION\u2014\u201cFORESTRY ACT, 1916.\u201d |newspaper=[[Government Gazette of the State of New South Wales]] |issue=215 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=29 August 1919 |page=4744 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The public has free access to the forest; it features two to four wheel drive tracks, creek crossings, and forest camping. It is popular among recreational trail bike riders.\n\n==History==\n\n===Murders===\nIn 1992 and 1993, seven skeletons were found in the forest, in what was described by media as the [[backpacker murders]] and was considered to be the work of a [[serial killer]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lennon|first1=Troy|title=Twenty five years ago the first victims of Backpacker Killer Ivan Milat were found in Belanglo Forest|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest-twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest/news-story/f4a31abad223faa68d8d73ca054d297e|accessdate=25 March 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=19 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-1/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 1)|date=2019-03-23|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Eventually, [[Ivan Milat]], an Australian of Croatian descent was convicted of the murders in 1996 and sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Frank|title=Milat's brother claims police still treating him as murder suspect|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/22/1085176039666.html?from=storylhs|accessdate=25 March 2019|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=23 May 2004}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 2010, three teenagers (including one related to Milat)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/teenage-relative-of-ivan-milat-charged-over-belanglo-forest-killing/story-e6frg6nf-1225958679503|title=Relative of Ivan Milat charged over Belanglo forest killing |date=22 November 2010|work=[[The Australian]]|accessdate=22 November 2010|first=Jodie|last=Minus}}</ref> were arrested on suspicion of connection with the discovery of a murdered male in the forest, following a tip-off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-5/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 5)|date=2019-04-20|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> David Auchterlonie was celebrating his 17th birthday on 20 November; Mathew Milat, 17, and Cohen Klein, 18 had planned for over a week to lure Auchterlonie to his death. A third person, Chase Day, 18 whose charges were later withdrawn by the DPP<ref>{{cite news|title=Someone's going to die: Belanglo teenager |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/someones-going-to-die-belanglo-teenager/story-e6frg6nf-1226175631030 |accessdate=21 April 2012 |newspaper=The Australian |date=25 October 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025065353/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/someones-going-to-die-belanglo-teenager/story-e6frg6nf-1226175631030 |archivedate=25 October 2011}}</ref> went to police midday 21 November to report the murder.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/national/milats-relative-charged-with-allegedly-killing-teen-david-auchterlonie-on-his-birthday/story-e6frf7l6-1225959257166|title=Milat's relative charged with allegedly killing teen David Auchterlonie on his birthday |date=23 November 2010|work=[[Herald Sun]]|accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== Other deaths ====\nOn 29 August 2010, trail bike riders discovered a human skeleton in the forest. Media reports at first linked the killing to Milat, but later forensic work disproved this theory as the remains were left there after he was in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/09/15/3012463.htm |title=Belanglo bones belong to teenage girl: police |date=15 September 2010 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref> On 21 October 2015, the bones were identified as the body of [[Karlie Pearce-Stevenson]], aged 22, from [[Alice Springs, Northern Territory]]. The body of Pearce-Stevenson's daughter, Khandalyce Pearce, aged 2, was found in a suitcase near [[Wynarka, South Australia]], on 14 July 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Detectives link Wynarka girl\u2019s bones in suitcase to \u2018Angel\u2019 bones in Belanglo|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/detectives-link-wynarka-girls-bones-in-suitcase-to-angel-bones-in-belanglo/story-fni0cx12-1227576865065|accessdate=22 October 2015|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n[[Category:New South Wales state forests]]\n\n{{NewSouthWales-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox forest\n| name          = \n| native_name   = \n| native_lang   =  \n| native_name2  = \n| native_lang2  = \n| photo         = Belanglo State Forest.jpg\n| photo_caption = \n| photo_width   = \n| map           = \n| map_caption   = \n| map_width     = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|-34.531146|150.260049|format=dms}}\n| coords_ref    = \n| county        = [[New South Wales]]\n| region        = [[Southern Highlands (New South Wales)|Southern Highlands]]\n| country       = Australia\n| elevation     = \n| area          =  \n| max_area      = \n| date_max_area = \n| status        = \n| established   = 1919\n| visitation    = \n| visitation_year = \n| events        = \n| authority     = [[Forestry Corporation]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Belanglo State Forest|url=http://www.forestrycorporation.com.au/new/visit/forests/belanglo|website=Forestry Corporation|language=en}}</ref>\n| website       = \n| ecosystem     = \n| classification_WWF = \n| classification_EPA =\n| classification_CEC = \n| disturbance   = \n| forest_cover  = \n| species       = [[Pine]]\n| indicator_plants = \n| lesser_flora  =  \n| fauna         = \n}}\n\n[[File:Belanglo State Forest sign.jpg|thumb|right|400px|This sign at the entrance of the forest advises visitors to \"please be careful\".]]\n\n'''Belanglo State Forest''' is a planted forest, of mainly pine but some native forestry around the edges in the [[Australia]]n state of [[New South Wales]]; its total area is about 3,800 hectares.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazette.nsw.gov.au/pdfs/2008/2_May-Part_1b.pdf|title=Game and Feral Animal Control Act 2002|page=3037|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326192543/http://www.gazette.nsw.gov.au/pdfs/2008/2_May-Part_1b.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2012}}</ref> The Belanglo State Forest is located south of [[Berrima, New South Wales|Berrima]] in the [[Southern Highlands, New South Wales|Southern Highlands]], three kilometres west of the [[Hume Highway]] between [[Sydney]] and [[Canberra]]. The forest is owned by the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]] and contains some of the earliest [[pine]] plantings in the state. The first [[Pinus radiata|radiata pines]] were planted in this area in 1919.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article222513200 |title=PROCLAMATION\u2014\u201cFORESTRY ACT, 1916.\u201d |newspaper=[[Government Gazette of the State of New South Wales]] |issue=215 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=29 August 1919 |page=4744 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The public has free access to the forest; it features two to four wheel drive tracks, creek crossings, and forest camping. It is popular among recreational trail bike riders.\n\n==History==\n\n===Murders===\nIn 1992 and 1993, seven skeletons were found in the forest, in what was described by media as the [[backpacker murders]] and was considered to be the work of a [[serial killer]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lennon|first1=Troy|title=Twenty five years ago the first victims of Backpacker Killer Ivan Milat were found in Belanglo Forest|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest-twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest/news-story/f4a31abad223faa68d8d73ca054d297e|accessdate=25 March 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=19 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-1/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 1)|date=2019-03-23|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Eventually, [[Ivan Milat]], an Australian of Croatian descent was convicted of the murders in 1996 and sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Frank|title=Milat's brother claims police still treating him as murder suspect|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/22/1085176039666.html?from=storylhs|accessdate=25 March 2019|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=23 May 2004}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 2010, three teenagers (including one related to Milat)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/teenage-relative-of-ivan-milat-charged-over-belanglo-forest-killing/story-e6frg6nf-1225958679503|title=Relative of Ivan Milat charged over Belanglo forest killing |date=22 November 2010|work=[[The Australian]]|accessdate=22 November 2010|first=Jodie|last=Minus}}</ref> were arrested on suspicion of connection with the discovery of a murdered male in the forest, following a tip-off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-5/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 5)|date=2019-04-20|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> David Auchterlonie was celebrating his 17th birthday on 20 November; Mathew Milat, 17, and Cohen Klein, 18 had planned for over a week to lure Auchterlonie to his death. A third person, Chase Day, 18 whose charges were later withdrawn by the DPP<ref>{{cite news|title=Someone's going to die: Belanglo teenager |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/someones-going-to-die-belanglo-teenager/story-e6frg6nf-1226175631030 |accessdate=21 April 2012 |newspaper=The Australian |date=25 October 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025065353/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/someones-going-to-die-belanglo-teenager/story-e6frg6nf-1226175631030 |archivedate=25 October 2011}}</ref> went to police midday 21 November to report the murder.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/national/milats-relative-charged-with-allegedly-killing-teen-david-auchterlonie-on-his-birthday/story-e6frf7l6-1225959257166|title=Milat's relative charged with allegedly killing teen David Auchterlonie on his birthday |date=23 November 2010|work=[[Herald Sun]]|accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== Other deaths ====\nOn 29 August 2010, trail bike riders discovered a human skeleton in the forest. Media reports at first linked the killing to Milat, but later forensic work disproved this theory as the remains were left there after he was in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/09/15/3012463.htm |title=Belanglo bones belong to teenage girl: police |date=15 September 2010 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref> On 21 October 2015, the bones were identified as the body of [[Karlie Pearce-Stevenson]], aged 22, from [[Alice Springs, Northern Territory]]. The body of Pearce-Stevenson's daughter, Khandalyce Pearce, aged 2, was found in a suitcase near [[Wynarka, South Australia]], on 14 July 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Detectives link Wynarka girl\u2019s bones in suitcase to \u2018Angel\u2019 bones in Belanglo|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/detectives-link-wynarka-girls-bones-in-suitcase-to-angel-bones-in-belanglo/story-fni0cx12-1227576865065|accessdate=22 October 2015|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n[[Category:New South Wales state forests]]\n\n{{NewSouthWales-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sumanuil", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belanglo_State_Forest"}
{"title_page": "Larry Storch", "text_new": "{{short description|American comedian}}\n           {{BLP sources|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Larry Storch\n| image         = File:Jerry Springer Larry Storch Geri Reischl 2011 David Shankbone (cropped).JPG\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Storch in 2011\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1923|1|8}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| birth_name    = Lawrence Samuel Storch\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| occupation    = Actor, voice actor, comedian\n| years_active  = 1939\u2013present\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Norma Catherine Greve|1961|2003|end=died}}\n| children      = 3\n}}\n\n'''Lawrence Samuel Storch''' (born January 8, 1923)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2018/01/08/UPI-Almanac-for-Monday-Jan-8-2018/2171515208436/|title= UPI Almanac for Monday, Jan. 8, 2018|agency= [[United Press International]]||date=January 8, 2018|accessdate=September 21, 2019| archivedate= January 8, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180108222931/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2018/01/08/UPI-Almanac-for-Monday-Jan-8-2018/2171515208436/|url-status=live|quote=\u2026comic actor Larry Storch in 1923 (age 95)}}</ref> is an American actor, voice actor, and comedian, best known for his comic television roles, including voice-over work for cartoon shows, such as Mr. Whoopee on ''[[Tennessee Tuxedo and His Tales]]'', and his live-action role of the bumbling Corporal Randolph Agarn on ''[[F Troop]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nStorch was born in [[New York City]], a son of Alfred Storch, a realtor, and his wife Sally (n\u00e9e Kupperman) Storch, a telephone operator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/87/Larry-Storch.html|title=Larry Storch profile|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=2010-08-26}}</ref> He attended [[DeWitt Clinton High School]] in the Bronx with [[Don Adams]], who remained his lifelong friend. Due to hard times in the [[Great Depression]], Storch said he never graduated from high school, instead finding work as a [[stand-up comic]] for $12 a week opening for bandleader [[Al Donahue]] at the band shell in [[Sheepshead Bay]].<ref name=\"Yost_Mark\">{{cite news|last=Yost|first= Mark|title=At Age 89, 'F Troop' Figure Holding the Fort on Acting.|url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304765304577481420287319152|accessdate=July 10, 2012|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=June 22, 2012}}{{subscription}}</ref>\n\nDuring World War II he served in the United States Navy where he was shipmates with [[Tony Curtis]] on the [[submarine tender]] [[USS Proteus (AS-19)|USS Proteus]]<ref>p. 13  Malone, Aubrey ''The Defiant One: A Biography of Tony Curtis'' McFarland, 21 Sep 2013</ref>.\n\n==Performing career==\nStorch was originally a [[Stand-up comedy|stand-up comic]]. This led to guest appearances on dozens of television series, including, ''[[Car 54, Where Are You?]]'', ''[[Hennesey]]'', ''[[Get Smart]]'', ''[[The Phil Silvers Show|Sergeant Bilko]]'', ''[[Columbo]]'', ''[[CHiPs]]'', ''[[Fantasy Island]]'', ''[[McCloud (TV series)|McCloud]]'', ''[[Emergency!]]'', ''[[The Flying Nun]]'', ''[[Alias Smith and Jones]]'', ''[[The Alfred Hitchcock Hour]]'', ''[[That Girl]]'', ''[[I Dream of Jeannie]]'', ''[[Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.]]'', ''[[Gilligan's Island]]'', ''[[The Doris Day Show]]'', ''[[The Persuaders!|The Persuaders]]'', ''[[Love, American Style]]'', ''[[All in the Family]]'', and ''[[Kolchak: The Night Stalker]]''.\n\n[[File:F Troop cast 1965.JPG|thumb|left|Storch, top right, with F-Troop cast (1965)]]\nHis most famous role was the scheming Corporal Randolph Agarn on the situation comedy ''[[F Troop]]'' (1965\u20131967), with [[Forrest Tucker]], [[Ken Berry]] and [[Melody Patterson]].\n\nIn 1975, Storch co-starred with [[Bob Burns III|Bob Burns]] (who was disguised as a gorilla) and Forrest Tucker on the short-lived but popular Saturday morning children's show ''[[The Ghost Busters]]''. He also appeared on ''[[The Love Boat]]'', was Al Bundy's childhood hero on ''[[Married... with Children]]'', and was a semi-regular on ''[[Car 54, Where Are You?]]''. He co-starred on the short-lived series ''[[The Queen & I (U.S. TV series)|The Queen and I]]''.\n\n==Variety show appearances==\nStorch appeared on many variety shows, including ''[[The Sonny & Cher Comedy Hour|Sonny and Cher]]'', ''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In|Laugh-In]]'', ''[[Hollywood Squares]]'', ''[[Playboy After Dark]]'' and ''[[The Hollywood Palace]]'', with several appearances on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'', ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'' and ''[[The Steve Allen Show]]''. [[Jackie Gleason]] personally asked Storch to fill in for him in the summer of 1953 while Gleason was on hiatus. This led to the 10-episode ''[[The Larry Storch Show]]'' with guest stars including [[Janet Blair]], [[Ris\u00eb Stevens]], [[Dick Haymes]] and [[Cab Calloway]].\n\n==As an impressionist and voiceover actor==\nAn impressionist, Storch does hundreds of voices and dialects ranging from [[Muhammad Ali]] to [[Claude Rains]]. This has proved useful for cartoons. He has voiced characters in numerous television and film animations including ''[[The Batman/Superman Hour]]'', ''[[The Pink Panther Show]]'', ''[[Groovie Goolies]]'', ''[[The Inspector]]'', ''[[The Brady Kids]]'', ''[[Cool Cat (film)|Cool Cat]]'', ''[[Koko the Clown]]'', ''[[Treasure Island]]'' and ''[[Tennessee Tuxedo]]''.\n\nStorch had worked with [[Mel Blanc]] and [[June Foray]] at [[Warner Bros.-Seven Arts]], voicing characters such as titular [[Merlin the Magic Mouse]] and [[Cool Cat (Looney Tunes)|Cool Cat]]. He continued his association with [[Filmation]] as a voiceover actor in other series and films the company produced including ''[[Journey Back to Oz]]'' where he voiced Aunt Em and Uncle Henry's farmhand Amos.\n\n==Film appearances==\nStorch has appeared in more than 25 [[Hollywood]] films, including ''[[Who Was That Lady?]]'' (1960), ''[[40 Pounds of Trouble]]'' (1962), ''[[Captain Newman, M.D.]]'' (1963), ''[[Wild and Wonderful]]'' (1964), ''[[Sex and the Single Girl (film)|Sex and the Single Girl]]'' (1964) and ''[[The Great Race]]'' (1965), all starring [[Tony Curtis]]. He also appeared in ''[[Bus Riley's Back in Town]]'' (1965), ''[[A Very Special Favor]]'' (1965), ''[[That Funny Feeling]]'', (1965), ''[[The Great Bank Robbery (1969 film)|The Great Bank Robbery]]'' (1969), ''[[Airport 1975]]'' (1974), ''[[The Happy Hooker Goes to Washington]]'' (1977), ''[[Record City]]'' (1978), ''[[S.O.B. (1981 film)|S.O.B]]'' (1981), ''Fake-Out'' (1982), ''[[Sweet Sixteen (1983 film)|Sweet Sixteen]]'' (1983) and ''[[A Fine Mess (film)|A Fine Mess]]'' (1986), as well as the cult sci-fi films ''[[The Monitors (film)|The Monitors]]'' (1969) and ''[[Without Warning (1980 film)|Without Warning]]'' (1980). Tony Curtis and Storch reunited for a 2003 run of the [[musical theatre|musical]] version of ''[[Sugar (musical)|Some Like It Hot]]''. In 2005, he worked with Anthony Michael Hall in ''Funny Valentine'' (2005), and appeared in the documentary feature ''[[The Aristocrats (film)|The Aristocrats]]'' (2005).\n\n==Stage work==\nAfter success in television and films, Storch returned to the New York stage, having first performed on the Broadway stage in the 1950s.<ref>{{IBDB name|61259|Larry Storch}}</ref> He received rave reviews for the Off-Broadway production of ''Breaking Legs''. Co-starring [[Philip Bosco]] and [[Vincent Gardenia]], the show extended several times before going on the road. Storch appeared in the Broadway productions of ''Porgy and Bess'' (which Larry considers his favorite), ''Arsenic and Old Lace'' with [[Jean Stapleton]], and ''Annie Get Your Gun'' with [[Reba McEntire]]. He toured the United States and Europe with ''Porgy and Bess''.\n\nIn 2004, he was in ''Sly Fox'' with [[Richard Dreyfuss]] and his old friend [[Irwin Corey]]. Larry, then 81, and \"Professor\" Corey, 90, did eight shows a week. In March 2008, Storch celebrated his 50th anniversary performing on Broadway. His first Broadway appearance had been ''Who Was That Lady I Saw You With'', later made into a 1960 [[Who Was That Lady?|film]] starring [[Dean Martin]] and Tony Curtis, with Storch appearing.\n\nStorch and ''[[Dark Shadows]]'' star Marie Wallace appeared in ''[[Love Letters (play)|Love Letters]]'' by A.R. Gurney on June 24, 2012, a benefit performance for the Actor's Temple in New York City.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\nIn the summer of 2012, Storch appeared in a benefit performance of ''Love Letters'' with actress Diana Sowle (best known for her role as Mrs. Bucket in the original Willy Wonka film) in [[Farmville, Virginia]] to benefit The Tom Mix Rangers.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n==Comedy LPs==\nStorch recorded a comedy LP ''Larry Storch at The Bon Soir'' released by Jubilee in the 1960s. Other records include ''Larry Storch Reads Philip Roth's Epstein'' and singles such as ''Larry Storch Pooped/Eighth Wonder of the World'', ''Larry Storch / I'm Walkin''.\n\n==Recent work==\nStorch is now \"semi-retired\". He still travels the country meeting his fans at personal appearances. \n\nHe has a substantial social media presence with over 40,000 Facebook followers, a record for any male actor his age.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Personal life==\nStorch married actress Norma Catherine Greve on July 10, 1961. They remained married until her death at the age of 81 on August 28, 2003. Both briefly appeared in the made-for-television movie ''[[The Woman Hunter]]'' (1972). He has three children: a stepson, Lary May; a daughter, Candace Herman, the result of a brief encounter with his future wife, born in 1947 and given up for adoption (and later reunited); and a stepdaughter, June Cross, born in 1954 to Norma and Jimmy Cross (\"Stump\" of the song-and-dance team [[Stump and Stumpy]]).<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Martin Douglas|Douglas, Martin]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/21/nyregion/norma-storch-is-dead-at-81-subject-of-tv-documentary.html|title=Norma Storch Is Dead at 81. Subject of TV Documentary|work=[[The New York Times]]|quote=The truth was that Ms. Cross was the child of an affair Mrs. Storch had had with Jimmy Cross, a black song-and-dance man who was Stump in the well-known performing team Stump and Stumpy|date=2003-09-21|accessdate=2010-08-26}}</ref>\n\nStorch's younger brother, Jay (1924\u20131987), was an actor/voiceover performer under the name [[Jay Lawrence (actor)|Jay Lawrence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/jay-lawrence/person/70789/summary.html |title=Jay Lawrence on |publisher=Tv.com|accessdate=2010-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{IMDb name|id=0492817|name=Jay Lawrence profile|accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and tributes==\nStorch was nominated for a Primetime Emmy award in 1967 for Outstanding Continued Performance by an Actor in a Leading Role in a Comedy Series for \u201cF Troop\u201d. Storch lost to childhood friend Don Adams that year. Storch says he later remarked to Adams \u201cYou kept it on the block.\u201d\n\nAn episode of ''[[Animaniacs]]'' titled \"The Sound of Warners\", features a banner that says \"Larry Storch Days; Nov 13 & 14\".\n\n{{Portal|Biography|New York City|Los Angeles|California|Comedy|Film|Television|World War II}}\n\n[[Fort Lee, New Jersey]] Mayor [[Mark Sokolich]] named Storch as honorary Mayor for a Day on June 1, 2014. Storch had previously been honored by the local film commission for performing at the [[Riviera (nightclub)|Riviera nightclub]], which had closed 60 years earlier.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moss|first1=Linda|title=Fort Lee welcomes TV comedian Larry Storch as mayor for a day|url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/fort-lee-welcomes-tv-comedian-larry-storch-as-mayor-for-a-day-1.1027197?page=all|accessdate=June 2, 2014|newspaper=The Record|date=June 1, 2014}}</ref>\nHe received the 2013 Barrymore Award for Lifetime Achievement in Film and TV from the Fort Lee Film Commission. \n\nA Golden Palm Star on the [[Palm Springs, California]] [[Palm Springs Walk of Stars|Walk of Stars]] was dedicated to Storch in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comedian Larry Storch to join Palm Springs Walk of Stars|url=http://www.kesq.com/news/comedian-larry-storch-to-join-palm-springs-walk-of-stars/28084820|website=www.kesq.com|publisher=Gulf-California Broadcast Company|date=Sep 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nStorch was named an honorary citizen of Passaic, New Jersey on September 13, 2016. He also received a [[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Navy)|Distinguished Service Medal]] to recognize his [[World War II]] service.<ref name=\"Cowen-2016-09-13\">{{cite news|last1=Cowen|first1=Richard|title=Actor who played Passaic corporal in '60s sitcom 'F Troop' visits city for first time|url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/actor-who-played-passaic-corporal-in-60s-sitcom-f-troop-visits-city-for-first-time-video-1.1659882|accessdate=September 14, 2016|work=The Record|date=September 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2019, [[The Lambs]] honored Storch with their Shepherd\u2019s Award.\n\n[[Wild West City]], an amusement park in New Jersey, renamed one of their storefronts \u201cLarry Storch\u2019s Silver Dollar Saloon\u201d in his honor. \n\nStorch was named an Honorary Friar in early 2019 at a ceremony with [[Dick Cavett]] at the [[New York Friars Club]].\n\nOn his 97th birthday, Storch was presented with a Proclamation from the State of New York.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Film\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1951|| ''[[The Prince Who Was a Thief]]'' || ||\n|-\n|1958|| ''[[Gun Fever (film)|Gun Fever]]'' |