{"title_page": "Omar Haji Massale", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Omar Haji Massale<br>\u0639\u0645\u0631 \u062d\u0627\u062c\u064a \u0645\u0633\u0627\u0644\u064a\n| image               = Cumar Xaaji Masale.jpg\n| office              = Chief of Armed Forces\n| order               = 1st\n| allegiance          = {{flagicon|Somalia}} [[Federal Government of Somalia]]\n| branch              = [[Somali Armed Forces|Somali National Army]]\n| rank                = [[File:15-Somali Army-MG.svg|18px]] [[Major General]]\n| mawards             = Gold Medal for Bravery and Service<ref>{{cite book|title=AMISOM Review|date=Jan 2014|page=17|url=http://amisom-au.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Issue-13-AMISOM-Magazine.pdf}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Omar haji Masale''' was a commander of the Somali [[military]] in the [[Hiiraan]] Region, which is located in Central [[Somalia]].  Before he joined the military, he was a [[language]] [[teacher]].  He also became a Somali [[Minister of Defence]] and [[Minister of Health|health minister]].\n\nMasale was one of the commanding officers of the 1977 [[Ogaden War]]. Masale was the second deputy to the joint chiefs of staff and the head of the 2dn armored division (formerly 2nd  Brigade). He was the operation commander for most of the major territory advanced for somali army  forces at the early stage of Ogadeen war 1977,  under his command the cities of Godey, Qabridahar, Wardheer,  Dhagax buur and other vast area had fallen at the hands of Somalis. He was known very tough in military discipline and excellent commands & controls.\nHe was nicknamed Montgomery as the first general who wears black beret as chief of staff of the army.\nDuring his commanding he made thorough adjustment of a nation's military to achieve a specified objective\u2014analyzes and laid new Somalaia military blue print book comprised: force structure, modernization, readiness, and sustainability.\nDespite his complex character, General Masale remains one of the best-known generals and one of the Somali Army's greatest ever commanders.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Somali people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n\n\n{{somalia-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n\n'''Omar haji Masale''' was a commander of the Somali [[military]] in the [[Hiiraan]] Region, which is located in Central [[Somalia]].  Before he joined the military, he was a [[language]] [[teacher]].  He also became a Somali [[Minister of Defence]] and [[Minister of Health|health minister]].\n\nMasale was one of the commanding officers of the 1977 [[Ogaden War]]. Masale was the second deputy to the joint chiefs of staff and the head of the 2dn armored division (formerly 2nd  Brigade). He was the operation commander for most of the major territory advanced for somali army  forces at the early stage of Ogadeen war 1977,  under his command the cities of Godey, Qabridahar, Wardheer,  Dhagax buur and other vast area had fallen at the hands of Somalis. He was known very tough in military discipline and excellent commands & controls.\nHe was nicknamed Montgomery as the first general who wears black beret as chief of staff of the army.\nDuring his commanding he made thorough adjustment of a nation's military to achieve a specified objective\u2014analyzes and laid new Somalaia military blue print book comprised: force structure, modernization, readiness, and sustainability.\nDespite his complex character, General Masale remains one of the best-known generals and one of the Somali Army's greatest ever commanders.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Somali people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n\n\n{{somalia-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sholi22", "label": "safe", "comment": "klsjdflekdewrwejroui", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omar_Haji_Massale"}
{"title_page": "Dwight Loftis", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Dwight Loftis\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| state_senate     = South Carolina\n| district         = 6th\n| term_start       = March 27, 2019\n| term_end         =\n| predecessor      = [[William Timmons]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=861409 |title=SC State Senate 06 - Special Election |website=Our Campaigns |access-date=April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n| successor        =\n| state_house1     = South Carolina\n| district1        = 19th\n| term_start1      = January 24, 1996\n| term_end1        = March 27, 2019\n| predecessor1     = [[Mike Fair]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=560111 |title=SC State House 019 - Special Election |website=Our Campaigns |access-date=April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n| successor1       = Patrick B. Haddon<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=850029 |title=SC State House 019 |website=Our Campaigns |access-date=April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n| prior_term       =\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1943|2|4}}\n| birth_place      = [[Greenville County, South Carolina]], United States\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| profession       = \n| religion         =\n| party            = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Dwight Loftis''' (born February 4, 1943) is an [[American people|American]] politician from [[South Carolina]]. A member of the [[South Carolina Senate]] since 2019, he previously represented district 19 in the [[South Carolina House of Representatives]] for 23 years from 1996 to 2019. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] party.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dwight Loftis|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/3981/dwight-loftis|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=April 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nLoftis became the Republican nominee for South Carolina Senate district 6 on January 22, 2019 by beating opponents Amy Ryberg Doyle and Jeffery Stringer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Loftis wins SC Senate District 6 Republican primary, according to unofficial vote total |url=https://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/news/local/2019/01/22/sc-senate-district-6-republican-primary-election-results/2617495002/ |publisher=Greenville News |access-date=April 4, 2020 |first=Kirk |last=Brown |date=January 22, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nHe won his state senate district 6 election with 56 percent of the votes against Democrat Tina Belge who received 44 percent of the votes in her first run for elected office.\n\nLoftis opposes to gay marriage and strongly supports marriage as defined between a man and woman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dwightloftis.com/issues |title=Issues |website=Dwight Loftis for Senate |language=en-US |access-date=February 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219072938/https://dwightloftis.com/issues |archive-date=February 19, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe voted to keep the [[Modern display of the Confederate battle flag|Confederate Flag]] flying above the South Carolina Statehouse.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.charlestoncitypaper.com/TheBattery/archives/2015/07/09/here-are-the-20-lawmakers-who-voted-against-removing-the-confederate-flag |title=Here are the 20 lawmakers who voted against removing the Confederate flag |website=Charleston City Paper |language=en-us |access-date=April 4, 2020 |first=Paul |last=Bowers |date=July 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|dwightloftis}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-sc-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Fair]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[South Carolina House of Representatives]]<br />from the 19th district|years=1996\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=Patrick B. Haddon}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-sc-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Timmons]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[South Carolina Senate]]<br>from the 6th district|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South Carolina State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loftis, Dwight}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the South Carolina House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Greenville County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{SouthCarolina-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Dwight Loftis\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| state_senate     = South Carolina\n| district         = 6th\n| term_start       = March 27, 2019\n| term_end         =\n| predecessor      = [[William Timmons]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=861409 |title=SC State Senate 06 - Special Election |website=Our Campaigns |access-date=April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n| successor        =\n| state_house1     = South Carolina\n| district1        = 19th\n| term_start1      = January 24, 1996\n| term_end1        = March 27, 2019\n| predecessor1     = [[Mike Fair]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=560111 |title=SC State House 019 - Special Election |website=Our Campaigns |access-date=April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n| successor1       = Patrick B. Haddon<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=850029 |title=SC State House 019 |website=Our Campaigns |access-date=April 4, 2020 }}</ref>\n| prior_term       =\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1943|2|4}}\n| birth_place      = [[Greenville County, South Carolina]], United States\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| profession       = \n| religion         =\n| party            = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Dwight Loftis''' (born February 4, 1943) is an [[American people|American]] politician from [[South Carolina]]. A member of the [[South Carolina Senate]] since 2019, he previously represented district 19 in the [[South Carolina House of Representatives]] for 23 years from 1996 to 2019. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] party.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dwight Loftis|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/3981/dwight-loftis|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=April 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nLoftis became the Republican nominee for South Carolina Senate district 6 on January 22, 2019 by beating opponents Amy Ryberg Doyle and Jeffery Stringer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Loftis wins SC Senate District 6 Republican primary, according to unofficial vote total |url=https://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/news/local/2019/01/22/sc-senate-district-6-republican-primary-election-results/2617495002/ |publisher=Greenville News |access-date=April 4, 2020 |first=Kirk |last=Brown |date=January 22, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nHe won his state senate district 6 election with 56 percent of the votes against Democrat Tina Belge who received 44 percent of the votes in her first run for elected office.\n\nLoftis is an opponent to gay marriage and strongly supports marriage as defined between a man and woman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dwightloftis.com/issues |title=Issues |website=Dwight Loftis for Senate |language=en-US |access-date=February 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219072938/https://dwightloftis.com/issues |archive-date=February 19, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe voted to keep the [[Modern display of the Confederate battle flag|Confederate Flag]] flying above the South Carolina Statehouse.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.charlestoncitypaper.com/TheBattery/archives/2015/07/09/here-are-the-20-lawmakers-who-voted-against-removing-the-confederate-flag |title=Here are the 20 lawmakers who voted against removing the Confederate flag |website=Charleston City Paper |language=en-us |access-date=April 4, 2020 |first=Paul |last=Bowers |date=July 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|dwightloftis}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-sc-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Fair]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[South Carolina House of Representatives]]<br />from the 19th district|years=1996\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=Patrick B. Haddon}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-sc-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Timmons]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[South Carolina Senate]]<br>from the 6th district|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South Carolina State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loftis, Dwight}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the South Carolina House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Greenville County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{SouthCarolina-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Adavidb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:simplified wording of the start of a sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwight_Loftis"}
{"title_page": "Ada Herefords", "text_new": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n|name             = Ada Herefords\n|allyears         = 1947\u20131954   \n|city             = Ada, Oklahoma\n|misc             =\n|logo             = \n|uniformlogo      = \n|class level      =  \n|past class level =  Class D (1947\u20131954)\n|current league   = \n|conference       =\n|division         = \n|past league      =  [[Sooner State League]] (1947\u20131954)\n|majorleague      = \n|pastmajorleague  = [[St. Louis Browns]] (1947\u20131953)<br> [[Baltimore Orioles]] (1954)\n|nickname         = \n|pastnames        =  '''Ada Herefords''' (1947\u20131954)<br>Ada Cementers (1954)<br>\n|ballpark         = \n|pastparks        =Hereford Park (1947\u20131954)\n|leaguechamps     = None\n|divisionchamps   = 1950\n|owner            = \n|manager          = \n|gm               =\n}}\nThe '''Ada Herefords''' was a  [[minor league baseball]] team based in [[Ada, Oklahoma]] from 1947\u20131954. Ada was a member of the Class D [[Sooner State League]], winning the league pennant in 1950. \n\nAda was an affiliate of the [[St. Louis Browns]] (1947\u20131953) and remained an affiliate when St. Louis relocated to become the [[Baltimore Orioles]] (1954).\n\n==History==\nMinor league baseball began in Ada, Oklahoma with the 1947 Ada Herefords. The Ada Herefords were charter members of the six-team [[Sooner State League]] in 1947, along with the [[Ardmore Indians]], [[Duncan Cementers]], [[Lawton Giants]], [[McAlester Rockets]] and [[Seminole Oilers]].<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Sooner_State_League Sooner State League - BR Bullpen<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=SO009 Sooner State League | The Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn their first season of play, the 1947 Ada Herefords finished 86-51 (2nd)  in the regular season as an affiliate of the [[St. Louis Browns]]. They would remain an affiliate of the Browns franchise throughout their existence.  In the 1947 playoffs, the  McAlester Rockets defeated the Ada Herefords 3 games to 2. The Ava season attendance was 41,872, an average of 611.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1947</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1947</ref>\n\nAda finished 63-76 (5th) in 1948 and did not qualify for the playoffs. The Sooner State League expanded from six-teams to eight-teams, adding the Chickasha Chiefs and [[Pauls Valley Raiders]] as expansion teams. The Ada season attendance in 1948 was 27,050.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1948</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1948</ref>\n\nThe Ava Herefords made the Sooner State League playoffs in 1949. Ava finished 69-70 (4th) in the regular season. In the playoffs, the Pauls Valley Raiders defeated Ada 3 games to 2. Season attendance was 33,525.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1949</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1949</ref>\n\nAda captured the Longhorn State League pennant in 1950. The Ada Herefords finished the regular season 1st with a 96-41 record, 5.5 games ahead of 2nd place McAlester Rockets. In the 1950 playoffs, the Ardmore Indians defeated Ada  3 games to 2. Season attendance was 31,981. <ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1950</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1950</ref>\n\nIn 1951, the Ada Herefords did not qualify for the playoffs. The Herefords finished 54-86 (5th) in the regular season. Attendance was 12,779,  an average of 183 per game.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1951</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1951</ref>\n\nAva again missed the playoffs in 1952, as the Herefords finished 57-82 (7th), drawing 38,387 for the season.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1952</ref><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1952</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nThe 1953 Ada Herefords advanced to the Sooner State League Finals. Ada finished 84-54 (3rd) in the regular season. In the 1953 playoffs, Ada had their first and only playoff series victory, as the Ada Herefords defeated the [[Shawnee Hawks]] 3 games to 1 in the semi-finals. In the \n\nFinals, the McAlester Rockets defeated Ada 4 games to 1 and captured the championship. Ada's season attendance was 36,128.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1953</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1953</ref>\n\nAda played their final minor league season in 1954, changing their moniker to the '''Ada Cementers''' in mid-season. The franchise became an affiliate of the Baltimore Orioles, as the St. Louis Browns had relocated to Baltimore in 1954. The Ada Herefords/Cementers finished 64-76\n(6th) in 1954, drawing 28,482, an average 407.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Ada_Herefords Ada Herefords - BR Bullpen<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1954</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1954</ref><ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nThe Ada Cementers permanently folded after the 1954. Fellow league member Pauls Valley Raiders folded also. They were replaced in the 1955 Sooner State League by the [[Muskogee Giants]] and [[Paris Orioles]]. Ada has not hosted another minor league team.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Ada,_OK Ada, OK - BR Bullpen<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Pauls_Valley_Raiders Pauls Valley Raiders - BR Bullpen<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==The ballpark==\nThe Ada Herefords played at '''Hereford Park'''. It is assumed the ballpark was located at the Pontotoc County fairgrounds.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-20</ref><ref>[http://digitalballparks.com/Browns.html St. Louis Browns Affiliation Listing of Major League Baseball Stadiums and Minor League Ballparks<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.pontotoccountyfairada.com/ Pontotoc County Free Fair<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Louis Brower]] (1953\u20131954, MGR)\n*[[Uke Clanton]] (1947\u20131948, MGR)\n*[[Stan Galle]] (1951, MGR)\n*[[Charlie Rabe]] (1952)\n\n*[[Joe Wood (1944 pitcher)|Joe Wood]] (1947) son of [[Smoky Joe Wood]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Season-by-season==\n(from [https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Ada_Herefords Baseball Reference])\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Record\n! Manager\n! Finish\n! Playoffs/Notes\n|-\n|1947 || 86\u201351 ||Uke Clanton|| 2nd || Lost in First Round\n|-\n|1948 || 63\u201376 || Uke Clanton ||5th || None\n|-\n|1949 || 69\u201370 ||Bill Krueger|| 4th || Lost in First Round\n|-\n|1950 || 96\u201341 ||Bill Krueger|| 1st || Lost in First Round\n|-\n|1951 || 54\u201356 || Stanley Galle || 5th || None\n|-\n|1952 || 57\u201382|| Bill Enos/Virl Loman/Jim England || 7th || None\n|-\n|1953 || 84\u201354 || [[Louis Brower]]|| 3rd || Lost League Finals\n|-\n|1954 || 64\u201376 ||Louis Brower / John Densmore || 6th || None\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External references==\n[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Ada_Herefords Baseball Reference]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Sports teams in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Browns minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Pontotoc County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Ada, Oklahoma]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n|name             = Ada Herefords\n|allyears         = 1947\u20131954   \n|city             = Ada, Oklahoma\n|misc             =\n|logo             = \n|uniformlogo      = \n|class level      =  \n|past class level =  Class D (1947\u20131954)\n|current league   = \n|conference       =\n|division         = \n|past league      =  [[Sooner State League]] (1947\u20131954)\n|majorleague      = \n|pastmajorleague  = [[St. Louis Browns]] (1947\u20131953)<br> [[Baltimore Orioles]] (1954)\n|nickname         = \n|pastnames        =  '''Ada Herefords''' (1947\u20131954)<br>Ada Cementers (1954)<br>\n|ballpark         = \n|pastparks        =Hereford Park (1947\u20131951, 1954\u20131957)\n|leaguechamps     = None\n|divisionchamps   = 1950\n|owner            = \n|manager          = \n|gm               =\n}}\nThe '''Ada Herefords''' was a  [[minor league baseball]] team based in [[Ada, Oklahoma]] from 1947\u20131954. Ada was a member of the Class D [[Sooner State League]], winning the league pennant in 1950. \n\nAda was an affiliate of the [[St. Louis Browns]] (1947\u20131953) and remained an affiliate when St. Louis relocated to become the [[Baltimore Orioles]] (1954).\n\n==History==\nMinor league baseball began in Ada, Oklahoma with the 1947 Ada Herefords. The Ada Herefords were charter members of the six-team [[Sooner State League]] in 1947, along with the [[Ardmore Indians]], [[Duncan Cementers]], [[Lawton Giants]], [[McAlester Rockets]] and [[Seminole Oilers]].<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Sooner_State_League Sooner State League - BR Bullpen<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=SO009 Sooner State League | The Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn their first season of play, the 1947 Ada Herefords finished 86-51 (2nd)  in the regular season as an affiliate of the [[St. Louis Browns]]. They would remain an affiliate of the Browns franchise throughout their existence.  In the 1947 playoffs, the  McAlester Rockets defeated the Ada Herefords 3 games to 2. The Ava season attendance was 41,872, an average of 611.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1947</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1947</ref>\n\nAda finished 63-76 (5th) in 1948 and did not qualify for the playoffs. The Sooner State League expanded from six-teams to eight-teams, adding the Chickasha Chiefs and [[Pauls Valley Raiders]] as expansion teams. The Ada season attendance in 1948 was 27,050.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1948</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1948</ref>\n\nThe Ava Herefords made the Sooner State League playoffs in 1949. Ava finished 69-70 (4th) in the regular season. In the playoffs, the Pauls Valley Raiders defeated Ada 3 games to 2. Season attendance was 33,525.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1949</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1949</ref>\n\nAda captured the Longhorn State League pennant in 1950. The Ada Herefords finished the regular season 1st with a 96-41 record, 5.5 games ahead of 2nd place McAlester Rockets. In the 1950 playoffs, the Ardmore Indians defeated Ada  3 games to 2. Season attendance was 31,981. <ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1950</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1950</ref>\n\nIn 1951, the Ada Herefords did not qualify for the playoffs. The Herefords finished 54-86 (5th) in the regular season. Attendance was 12,779,  an average of 183 per game.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1951</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1951</ref>\n\nAva again missed the playoffs in 1952, as the Herefords finished 57-82 (7th), drawing 38,387 for the season.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1952</ref><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1952</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nThe 1953 Ada Herefords advanced to the Sooner State League Finals. Ada finished 84-54 (3rd) in the regular season. In the 1953 playoffs, Ada had their first and only playoff series victory, as the Ada Herefords defeated the [[Shawnee Hawks]] 3 games to 1 in the semi-finals. In the \n\nFinals, the McAlester Rockets defeated Ada 4 games to 1 and captured the championship. Ada's season attendance was 36,128.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1953</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1953</ref>\n\nAda played their final minor league season in 1954, changing their moniker to the '''Ada Cementers''' in mid-season. The franchise became an affiliate of the Baltimore Orioles, as the St. Louis Browns had relocated to Baltimore in 1954. The Ada Herefords/Cementers finished 64-76\n(6th) in 1954, drawing 28,482, an average 407.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Ada_Herefords Ada Herefords - BR Bullpen<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1954</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ah10022/y-1954</ref><ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nThe Ada Cementers permanently folded after the 1954. Fellow league member Pauls Valley Raiders folded also. They were replaced in the 1955 Sooner State League by the [[Muskogee Giants]] and [[Paris Orioles]]. Ada has not hosted another minor league team.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Ada,_OK Ada, OK - BR Bullpen<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Pauls_Valley_Raiders Pauls Valley Raiders - BR Bullpen<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==The ballpark==\nThe Ada Herefords played at '''Hereford Park'''. It is assumed the ballpark was located at the Pontotoc County fairgrounds.<ref>https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-20</ref><ref>[http://digitalballparks.com/Browns.html St. Louis Browns Affiliation Listing of Major League Baseball Stadiums and Minor League Ballparks<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.pontotoccountyfairada.com/ Pontotoc County Free Fair<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Louis Brower]] (1953\u20131954, MGR)\n*[[Uke Clanton]] (1947\u20131948, MGR)\n*[[Stan Galle]] (1951, MGR)\n*[[Charlie Rabe]] (1952)\n\n*[[Joe Wood (1944 pitcher)|Joe Wood]] (1947) son of [[Smoky Joe Wood]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Season-by-season==\n(from [https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Ada_Herefords Baseball Reference])\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Record\n! Manager\n! Finish\n! Playoffs/Notes\n|-\n|1947 || 86\u201351 ||Uke Clanton|| 2nd || Lost in First Round\n|-\n|1948 || 63\u201376 || Uke Clanton ||5th || None\n|-\n|1949 || 69\u201370 ||Bill Krueger|| 4th || Lost in First Round\n|-\n|1950 || 96\u201341 ||Bill Krueger|| 1st || Lost in First Round\n|-\n|1951 || 54\u201356 || Stanley Galle || 5th || None\n|-\n|1952 || 57\u201382|| Bill Enos/Virl Loman/Jim England || 7th || None\n|-\n|1953 || 84\u201354 || [[Louis Brower]]|| 3rd || Lost League Finals\n|-\n|1954 || 64\u201376 ||Louis Brower / John Densmore || 6th || None\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External references==\n[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Ada_Herefords Baseball Reference]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Sports teams in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Browns minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Pontotoc County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Ada, Oklahoma]]\n", "name_user": "Skilgis1900", "label": "safe", "comment": "infobox edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ada_Herefords"}
